column168: DRIVER WITH INBOUND DRUM LOAD NOTICED A LEAKER AND CAME IN EARLY.  TWO LEAKING DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED WITH ABOUT 1 GAL OF MATERIAL RELEASED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE 2 DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND ALL MATERIAL RECOVERED USING OIL SOAK.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS NOPBRR CARMAN SMELLED ODOR AROUND A BLOCK OF TANK CARS IN OUR COTTON WAREHOUSE YARD.  NOPBRR SUPERVISOR DUPLECHAIN WAS NOTIFIED OF SITUATION AT WHICH TIME NOPBRR HAZ-MAT RESPONSE PROCEDURES WERE IMPLEMENTED.  ALL PROPER AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED AT 1005 HOURS. SUPERVISOR RANSON ACCOMPANIED NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ-MAT PERSONNEL TO CAR AND FOUND TOP COVER BOLTS LOOSE.  (SIX BOLT COVER, ALL LOOSE).  AAR-BOE REPRESENTATIVE. ERNEWIN INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND CAR SAFE TO MOVE TO DESTINATION.  ALL PARTIES MET AT CAR SITE AND AGREED THAT CAR WAS SAFE AND COULD CONTINUE TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION.  THIS CAR WAS BEING SHIPPED FROM THE BNSF RR VIA THE NOPB RR TO THE NORFOLK SOUTHERN. BOTH RAILROADS WERE NOTIFIED OF SITUATION.
PERSONNEL CLEARED FROM AREA.  PPE PUT ON.  REMOVED DAMAGED MATERIAL TO PSC.  PROCESSED PKG USING DECISION TREE/CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET AND H/M RESPONSE PROCEDURE.  PH TESTED AT 13.

PERSONNEL CLEARED FROM_A_E_._ PPE PUT ON.  REMOVED DAMAGED MATERIAL TO PSC.  PROCESSED PKG USING DECISION TREE/FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET AND HAZ MAT RESPONSE PROCEDURE.  DISPOSED OF WASTE THRU DMP.  CLEANED AND STORED EQUIPMENT.

column168: A PAIL OF CORROSIVE LIQUID ACIDIC ORGANIC ACID(CONTAINING HYDROXYACETIC ACID), A CLASS 8 LIQUID WAS DAMAGED DURING TRANSIT TO PRESTON'S SEEKONK, MASS TERMINAL.  A NAIL ON A PALLET HAD CAUSED A HOLE TO FORM ON THE BOTTOM OF THE PAIL.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE LOST.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND WASHED UP.  THE PAIL DISPOSED OF AND THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT DELIVERED CLEAR.

DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION A PINHOLE ON THE SEAM (WELD) ON THE FRONT BULKHEAD OF THE CARGO TANKER WAS FOUND.  THE HOLE WAS ABOVE THE LIQUID LEVEL WITH A SEEP EMERGING.  THE TANKER WAS WIPED DRY AND THE HOLE PLUGGED, THE TANKER WAS THEN UNLOADED.  THE CLOTH USED WAS DISPOSED OF IN A HAZARDOUS WASTE DRUM.  THE TANKER IS TO BE INSPECTED AND REPAIRED, THEN RETESTED.  PROBABLE CAUSE OF RELEASE IS A SEAM FAILURE IN THE RUBBER LINING WHICH PERMITTED A SMALL QUANTITY OF ACID TO CONTACT THE SHELL AND DEVELOP A PINHOLE.  WILL CONTINUE REGULAR INSPECTIONS AND TESTING OF CARGO TANKER.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZ WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM MERRILATT INDUSTRIES, INC LOCATED AT 641 MADDOX DR IN CULPEPER, VA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC LOACATED AT 385 QUINCY AVE IN BRAINTREE, MA.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVE IN CINCINNATI, OH, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPX 1-2 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL CLEANUP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  AN INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION IDENTIFIED THAT AN AREA OF THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE CONTAINER WAS CORRODED WHICH ALLOWED THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE CONTAINER.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED BY THE DRIVER.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT EACH CONTAINER ACCEPTED FOR TRANSPORTATION IS IN SHIPPABLE CONDITION.  ANY CONTAINER FOUND TO BE IN UNSHIPPABLE CONDITION MUST BE EITHER REPACKAGED OR PLACED INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZ WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO LOCATED AT DEKA RD IN LYON STATION, PA, TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC LOCATED AT 11800 S STONEY ISLAND AVE IN CHICAGO, IL.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY INC, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPX 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP BUNG CAP OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE LEAKING CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEANUP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  AN INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING CONTAINER IDENTIFIED THAT THE BUNG CAP HAD A SMALL HOLE IN IT WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM THE CONTAINER.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL CONTAINERS ARE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING TO INSURE ALL CLOSURE DEVICES ARE SECURED AND IN PROPER WORKING ORDER.

column14: PARKING LOT OFF OF 604 MAIN ST
column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: NO PACKAGING FAILURE ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  TANK OVERFILL.  SEARS OIL CO DISPATCHED J A CARMAN TRUCKING CO INC TO DELIVER 7,500 GAL OF #2 HEATING OIL FOR DELIVER ON 1/15/97 TO THE MT ANTHONY SCHOOL IN BENNINGTON, VT.  OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE SCHOOL AT 6:30 PM AND CHECKED IN WITH THE CUSTODIAN.  OUR DRIVER STUCK THE TANK WITH THE CUSTODIAN AND CONFIRMED THAT THE LOAD WOULD FIT.  AS THE LAST OF THE OIL WAS DRAINING OFF OUR TRAILER, THE UST OVERFILLED AND OIL CAME OUT THE VENT.  ABOUT 20 GALS OF OIL SPILLED ONTO THE SNOW WHICH COVERED THE CEMENT PARKING LOT.  SPILL RESPONSE CREWS WERE SENT TO THE SITE AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP.  EXACT CAUSE OF OVERFILL IS UNKNOWN.  MOST PROBABLE EXPLANATION IS THE UST IS NOT LEVEL CAUSING INACCURATE GAUGING.  SCHOOL OFFICIALS ARE HAVING THE UST EVALUATED BY CO THAT INSTALLED IT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZ WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CITIZENS BANK OF MD LOCATED AT 14401 SWEITZER LA IN LAUREL, MD TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES INC LOCATED AT 11800 S STONEY ISLAND AVE IN CHICAGO, IL.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY INC LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVE IN CINCINNATI, OH, THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION WAS BEING MOVED FROM ONE VEHICLE TO ANOTHER FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION.  DURING THIS TRANSFER OPERATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1-2 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP LID OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER INDICATED THAT THE TOP CLOSURE WAS LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND TRANSFERRED THE CONTENTS OF THE LEAKING DRUM INTO A SUITABLE NON REMOVABLE HEAD CONTAINER. ALL CLEANUP DEBRIS ASSOCIATED WITH THE CLEANUP EFFORTS WERE DISPOSED OF AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY INC.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS NOT SECURED PROPERLY PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: OUR LOGEX DRIVER WAS TRAVELLING WEST ON VALLEY VIEW ENTERING THE INTERSECTION WITH LEFFINGWELL. V2 TRAVELING SOUTH OF LEFFINGWELL ENTERED THE INTERSECTION AND STRUCK THE RIGHT SIDE OF OUR TRACTOR. THE TRACTOR TRAILER VEERED TO THE SOUTH (LEFT), STRUCT A HIGHWAY CONCRETE MEDIAN, TURNING ISLAND. UPON IMPACT WITH THE 6" HIGH CONCRETE CURB, THE KING PIN BROKE, ALLOWING THE UNIT TO SEPARATE AND THE TRAILER ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE, THE TRACTOR REMAINED UPRIGHT. THE DRIVER AND ONLY OCCUPANT OF V2 SUFFERED A BROKEN LEFT SHOULDER FROM THE COLLISION. THE TRAILER MAINTAINED ITS INTEGRITY, THE LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS ATTRIBUTED TO TRANSFER OF PRODUCT TO AN EMPTY TRAILER AND NORMAL PRESSURE RISE AND VENTING. EVACUATION - WE LEARNED OF AN EVACUATION THE FOLLOWING DAY FROM NEWS REPORT - LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT PERSONNEL TOOK IT UPON THEMSELVES TO EVACUATE - THEY HAD NO KNOWLEDGE OF THE PRODUCT.

column168: ON 1/6/97 AT APPROXIMATELY 18:00, DRIVER OF VEH #1 ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S PLANT SITE, CHECKED MANIFOLD TO MAKE SURE HE WOULD NOT CONTAMINATE KEROSENE #1. WHEN HE OPENED THE MANIFOLD VALVE SOME DIESEL FUEL FROM THE PREVIOUS LOAD SPILLED OUT OVER HIS PAIL HITTING HIS LEG. THE DRIVER CHANGED HIS PANTS AT THE SCENE, BUT DID NOT HIS PAIL HITTING HIS LEG. THE DRIVER CHANGED HIS PANTS AT THE SCENE, BUT DID NOT CHANGE HIS SOCKS (HE DID NOT REALIZE THAT THE PRODUCT HAD GONE AS FAR AS HIS SOCKS). THERE WAS NO PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE GROUND. CHEMICAL BURNS TO THE ANKLE WHERE THE RESULT OF THE DRIVER DID CHANGING HIS STOCKINGS. PREVENTION: DRIVERS ARE TO CHECK MANIFOLDS WHEN DELIVERY IS COMPLETED AT THE DELIVERY SITE. IF FUEL IS PRESENT IT IS TO BE DRAINED OFF AND LEFT WITH CONSIGNEE. DRIVERS ARE TO BE INSTRUCTED TO CHANGE ALL AFFECTED CLOTHING WHEN INVOLVED WITH A SPILL.

ON 1/21/97, APPROXIMATELY 03:15, VEH #1 ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADING LOCATION. WHEN DRIVER REMOVED THE DUST CAP ON THE CARGO TANK'S UNLOADING VALVE, THE DRIVER FOUND THAT THE MOLTEN SULPHUR HAD LEAKED PAST THE WHEEL VALVE AND HAD COOLED, SETTING UP IN THE VALVE BONNET. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO UNPLUG THE VALVE. WHEN THE MOLTEN SULPHUR IN THE TANK THAWED THE SULPHUR THAT WAS PLUGGING THE OUTLET ON THE VALVE OF THE CARGO TANK, THE PRODUCT STARTED TO SPILL OUT OF THE OUTLET. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO REACH THE OUTLET VALVE HANDLE TO CUT OFF THE FLOW, HOWEVER, THE VALVE WAS NOT SEATED PROPERLY AND THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO CLOSE THE VALVE.

column168: IMPROPER INSTALLATION OF THIS ABOVE GROUND TANK CAUSED PRESSURE TO BUILD UP DURING DELIVERY TO THE POINT THAT A TOP SEAM FAILED, ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF GASOLINE TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND.  THIS TANK DID NOT HAVE THE REQUIRED AUDIBLE ALARM SOUND AT 90% CAPACITY.  ALSO, IN VIOLATION OF CODE, THE TANK'S OVERFILL PROTECTION SYSTEM RESTRICTED THE TANK'S VENT AND CAUSED PRESSURE TO BUILD INSIDE THE TANK.  FOLLOWING THE INSTRUCTIONS OF NORTH CAROLINA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH AND NATURAL RESOURCES, TEPC CO., REMOVED ABOUT 20 YARDS OF GRAVEL WHERE THE GAS HAD SPILLED.  FOUR SAMPLES OF DIRT WERE TAKEN AND TESTED PER DEHNR REQUIREMENTS.  THE RESULTS WERE LESS THAN TEN PARTS PER MILLION AND NO FURTHER ACTION WAS REQUIRED.  SINCE WE KNOW THAT THE TANKS AT THIS LOCATION DO NOT MEET, THE CODE, WE WILL MAKE NO FURTHER DELIVERIES HERE. WE CONSIDER THIS MATTER CLOSED WITH NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED UNLESS NOTIFIED OTHERWISE.

column168: AT 0415 I WAS CALLED TO WILMINGTON BOXLINE TO RESPOND TO A 5-PART FLAMMABLE LIQUID SPILL AT SLOT #2.  AT THE SCENE I VIEWED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  PUTTING ON PROPER PPE I CONTAINERIZED THE WET PACKAGE AND PUT SPEEDY DRI ON THE WET SUBSTANCE.  I CLEANED UP THE SPEEDY DRI AND PROCESSED THE PACKAGE THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM.

I RESPONDED TO SPILL WEARING PROPER PPE.  AFTER CORDONING AREA OFF, I DETERMINED THE SUBSTANCE TO BE A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, BY USING MY DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS.  AS PER RESPONSE SHEET, I KEPT ALL SOURCES OF IGNITION AWAY.  THERE WAS NO LIQUID TO CLEAN UP - CARDBOARD WAS DAMP, SO I SPREAD ACTIVATED CHARCOAL ON IT TO ELIMINATE ODOR.  I THEN REMOVED THE BOXES AND BOTTLE TO THE HAZ MAT CAGE WHERE I PROCESSED THE SOILD CARDBOARD THRU THE DMP PROGRAM AND REPACKAGED BOTTLE ACCORDING TO UPS SPECIFICATIONS AND RETURNED THEM TO THE SHIPPER.

I RESPONDED TO A LEAKING BOX WEARING PROPER PPE.  I USED MY DECISION TREE TO DETERMINE IF THE BOX WAS HAZARDOUS.  I REFERRED TO MY CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET AND THE MSDS.  THE PULLER GOT SOME OF THE LIQUID ON HER ARM AND PER MSDS SHE WASHED IT OFF IN WARM SOAPY WATER FOR 15 MINUTES.  THERE WAS STILL IRRITATION SO SHE WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL.  I APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO THE SPILLED LIQUID TILL TESTED BETWEEN 6 & 9 ON PH SCALE. I PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP AND RE-PACKED THE GOOD PORTION ACCORDING TO UPS SPECIFICATIONS AND RETURNED IT TO THE SHIPPER.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: DURING TRANSPORTATION WHSE DRIVER SMELLED A STRANGE ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  HE OPENED A SMALL DOOR ON REAR OF TRAILER AND DISCOVERED THE ODOR WAS FROM THE TRAILER.  HE CALLED IN AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO KEEP THE NOSE OF TRAILER IN A DOWNWARD POSITION TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT TO THE TRAILER, IN THEEVENT OF A LEAKAGE.  A HAZMAT TEAM FROM WEST TEXAS HAZMAT WAS SENT OUT TO CONTAIN ANY SPILLAGE.  REPORTS FROM THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND THE INDEPENDENT ADJUSTER INDICATED THAT THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN STACKED TOO HIGH BY THE SHIPPER, CAUSING THE LOWER CONTAINERS TO FAIL.

OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE WHEN THE CONSIGNEE'S EMPLOYEE MISTAKENLY OPENED THEIR INLET VALVE BEFORE OUR DELIVERY HOSE WAS CONNECTED WHICH RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF MATERIAL.  THE MATERIAL THAT WAS LOST CAME FROM THE CONSIGNEES STORAGE TANK AND WAS NOT PART OF THE MATERIAL THAT WE WERE DELIVIRING.

DURING THE UNLOADING OF OUR UNIT AT THE CONSIGNEE, A SMALL SEEPAGE OF MATERIAL WAS DISCOVERED AROUND THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  OUR DRIVER TIGHTENED THE FITTING WHICH STOPPED THE SEEPAGE AND THE UNLOADING WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.
THE DOCK PERSONNEL WERE REMOVING THE SKID OF PRODUCT WHEN THEY NOTICED THE BAG BOTTOM OPEN.  THEY SHOVELED UP THE PRODUCT AND PUT IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM.

DRIVER WAS AT UNLOADING LOCATION.  THE VENTILATION SYSTEM AT CUSTOMER LOCATION WAS MALFUNCTIONING.  THIS CAUSED A SPILL OF 4 GALLONS OF DIESEL. DRIVER SHUT OFF THE TRAILER VALVE AND USED HIS SPILL KIT TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  DRIVER WAS NOT AT FAULT.  CUSTOMER WILL CHECK THEIR EQUIPMENT TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES.
DRIVER WAS UNLOADING DRUM AND SLIGHTLY TILTED THEM.  AS SHE DID THIS, 2 OF THEM LEAKED AT THE CLOSURE ON THE TOP OF THE DRUMS, AND SPILLED ONTO HER CLOTHING.

THE 5 GALLON PAIL OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS BEING SHIPPED FROM MCGUIRE NUCLEAR STATION TO LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.  THE FIRST TRANSPORTER, DUKE POWER, TOOK THE WASTE MATERIAL TO TODDVILLE.  TODDVILLE IS A TEMPORARY STORAGE TERMINAL OPERATED BY DUKE POWER.  WHILE TAKING THE WASTE TO A TEMPORARY HOLDING AREA USING A FORKLIFT AND PALLET, ONE OF THE 5 GALLON PAILS FELL OFF OF THE PALLET.  BOTH THE PALLET AND FORKLIFT RAN OVER THE PAIL CAUSING IT TO BE CRUSHED.  THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED PRIOR TO THE SECOND TRANSPORTER, LAIDLAW, PICKING UP THE MATERIAL AND TAKING IT TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION, LAIDLAW'S FACILITY IN REIDSVILLE.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM AMTRAK LOCATED AT 202 GARSTANG AVE IN BEECHGROVE, INTO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVE IN CHICAGO, IL.  DURING A ROUTINE STOPAT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED IN THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER, WHERE IT WASPREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER INDICATED THAT SURFACE RUST WAS PRESENT AT THE SITE OF THE PINHOLE LEAK AND ITWEAKENED AT THIS LOCATION ALLOWING THE LEAK TO DEVELOP.  FACILITY PERSONNELIMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDY DRY, AND PLACED THE CONTAINER IN TO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN THIS SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.

SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO C-4 ON A POSSIBLE SPILL AT 0235L.  UPON ARRIVAL IN C-4 FOUND ONE BOX OUT OF A 21-PIECE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN STRUCK BY A FORKLIFT.  UPON INSPECTION OF BOX RESPONDERS FOUND THAT IT CONTAINED FOUR ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS CONTAINING A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  ONE OF THE GALLON JUGS HAD BEEN DAMAGED.  RESPONDERS CLEANED UP SPILL AND PLACED GALLON JUG IN A 55 GALLON DISPOSAL DRUM, AWAITING DISPOSITION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.
CTNS CAME IN WITH SOME DAMP SPOTS ON CTN.  FLOOR WAS NOT WET.  TOPS SEEMED TO HAVE WORKED LOOSE DURING TRANSIT.

OUR MAN UNLOADING IN DRIVING RAINSTORM IN HOUSTON, TEXAS.  PACKING ON PUMP LEAKED AND IT WAS OBSERVED AS LEAKING.  DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO LESSEN LEAK BY TIGHTENING PACKING.  ON FIRST ATTEMPT HE OVER TIGHTENED IT AND THEN UPON CHECKING, LOOSENED IT AND IT WAS TOO LOOSE CAUSING A SPILL.  HE SHUT DOWN, RETIGHTENED AND LEAK STOPPED.  CARRIER ASSISTED IN CLEANUP OF SPILL.

AS FRA INSPECTOR WAS CONDUCTING A ROUTINE INSPECTION AT CSTX'S RAIL YARD IN CUMBERLAND, MD AND FOUND A TANK CAR WITH SOME LIQUID PRODUCT RESIDUE UNDER THE LIQUID VALVE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND ON TOP OF THE CAR.  THERE WAS A NOTE PLACED ON TOP OF THE CAR THAT THE "PRESSURE RELEASE VALVE" HAD PRODUCT AROUND IT.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY SENT MARYLAND RAIL CAR TO INSPECT THE CAR.  MARYLAND RAIL REPLACED THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

TANK CAR REPORTED TO HAVE A VAPOR MIST RELEASE FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN AUGUSTA, GA.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. THE MOBILE UNIT FOUND THE CAR HAD A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK.  THE DISK WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

column168: WHILE CONDUCTING UNLOADING OPERATIONS AT ENVIRITE OF PENNSYLVANIA, INC. (A TREATMENT, STORAGE AND DISPOSAL FACILITY), IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 1 FIBERBOARD INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINER HAD LEAKED MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN/TRAILER.  THE RELEASE DID NOT CONSTITUTE A RELEASE FROM THE FACILITY AS THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE VAN/TRAILER. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDERS AT THE FACILITY CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL, ESTIMATED AT 6 TO 8LBS.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL, ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE SHIPMENT WAS PROCESSED AND TREATED AT THE ENVIRITE OF PA, INC TSD FACILITY (THE DESTINATION FACILITY ORIGINALLY DESIGNATED ON THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST-SEE ATTACHED).  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FAILURE OF THE PACKAGE WAS DUE TO MOISTURE FROM RAINWATER THAT HAD BEEN ABSORBED INTO THE PACKAGING MATERIAL DURING STORAGE.  AT THE TIME THE PACKAGES WERE LOADED FOR SHIPMENT, THERE WAS NO VISIBLE SIGN THAT THE STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY OF THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN COMPROMISED. IN ORDER TO AVOID FUTURE INCIDENTS TO THE EXTENT POSSIBLE, DRIVERS EMPLOYED BY ENVIRITE OF PA, INC WILL RECEIVE ADDITIONAL TRAINING COVERING INSPECTION OF PACKAGING, INCLUDING AREAS WHERE PACKAGES ARE STORED.  THE TRAINING WILL ALSO INCLUDE RECOGNITION OF FACTORS AND CIRCUMSTANCES THAT MAY CONTRIBUTE TO POTENTIAL FAILURE OF PACKAGING DURING LOADING, UNLOADING AND TRANSPORTATION.

column168: DRIVER PICKED UP THE HAZMAT SHIPMENT AND THEN WENT TO HIS NEXT STOP.  AT THE NEXT STOP, WOODGRAIN MILLWORK, THE FORKLIFT DRIVER ACCIDENTALLY PUNCTURED THE CARTON WITH THE FORKLIFT BLADES WHILE LOADING ANOTHER SHIPMENT.  AT THAT POINT, THE AREA WAS CLEARED, CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER, AND THE REGIONAL SAFETY DIRECTOR WERE CALLED.  OUR SUPERVISOR WAS DIRECTED BY OUR SAFETY DIRECTOR TO CALL S&S COMPANY IN ALBANY, GA TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE INCIDENT OVER AT 0100 ON THE 28TH.

column168: AN IBC WITH A CAPACITY OF 330 GL WAS LOADED WITH 300 GL OF 35% HYDROGEN PEROXIDE.  WHEN COMPANY DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS FIRST DELIVERY HE OPENED TRAILER DOOR AND OBSERVED A CLOUD OF FUMES.  HE NEXT OBSERVED A STREAM OF LIQUID COMING FROM FRONT OF TRAILER.  THE IBC WAS LOADED IN FRONT LEFT CORNER OF TRAILER.  DRIVER PUT ON PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND ENTERED TRAILER.  HE DETERMINED LEAK WAS COMING FROM IBC.  HE ALSO DETERMINED THAT HE COULD NOT STOP THE LEAK.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO USE THE ABSORBENT CARRIED IN TRUCK SPILL KIT TO DIKE THE PARKING LOT TRUCK WAS PARKED IN.  THIS PREVENTED SPILLED MATERIAL FROM REACHING SEWER.  BOULDER FIRE DEPT WAS SUMMONED AND TOOK CONTROL OF INCIDENT SCENE.  GREAT WESTERN CONTRACTED WITH SMITH ENVIRONMENTAL FOR SITE CLEAN UP.  AFTER SITE WAS CLEANED, WE WERE ABLE TO INSPECT THE IBC.  THE IBC WAS POLY BLADDER SURROUNDED BY A STEEL CAGE.  THE POLY BLADDER DEVELOPED A CRACK APPROXIMATELY 24 INCHES LONG ON THE SIDE NEAR THE BOTTOM.

ON JANUARY 8, 1997 AT APPROX. 1400 HOURS, CBL TRUCKING, INC. ACCIDENTALLY DISCHARGED APPROX. 50 GALLONS OF COMPOUND CLEANING LIQUID ONTO THE PARKING LOT AT THE CHESTER MALL IN CHESTER, NJ. column168: ON 01/19/97 TANK CAR UTLX 645881 (STYRENE MONOMER, INHIBITED,3,UN20555) WAS REPORTED LEAKING AT BNSF'S NORTH YARD IN FORT WORTH, TX.  BNSF RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED, ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE'S PACKING GLAND NUT WAS LOOSE CAUSING STYRENE TO LEAK AROUND THE VALVE HANDLE.  THE NUT WAS TIGHTENED, STOPPING THE LEAK.

ON 01/07/97 AT 0545 CREW OF TRAIN 02RR023 WAS NOTIFIED BY THE BNSF DISPATCHER THAT A TRUCK DRIVER STOPPED AT A CROSSING AND OBSERVED A TANK CAR LEAKING.  THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED AT MILEPOST 150, WHERE THE CAR BN974936 (DIESEL FUEL, COMBUSTILE LIQUID, NA1993) WAS INSPECTED BY BNSF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM MEMBERS.  THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE A FAILURE OF THE CAR'S INTERIOR HEATER COIL PIPES WERE THEY EXIT THE INTERIOR OF THE CAR.  THE LEAK WAS PLUGGED AND THE FUEL REMAINING IN THE TANK CAR WAS PUMPED INTO A TANK TRUCK.  BN974036 WAS SENT TO ITS HOME SHOP FOR REPAIR.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: ON 01/07/97, AT THE FERRELLGAS FACILITY, PRIOR TO UNLOADING TANK CAR GATX 55486 (PROPANE,2,1,UN1075) EMPLOYEES NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL GAS LEAK COMING FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WHERE IT IS BOLTED TO THE CAR. BNSF HAZMAT RESPONDER WAS REQUESTED TO INSPECT THE CAR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CAR, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR SHOULD BE UNLOADED AND THE CAR FORWARDED TO ITS HOME FOR REPAIR.  AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT, THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE IS STILL UNKNOWN.  GATX WILL PROVIDE A MAINTENANCE REPORT TO THE BNSF AFTER THEY COMPLETE THEIR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: IBC WAS PROPERTY BRACED & BLOCKED TO PREVENT HORIZONTAL MOTION.  AFTER VEHICLE PASSED THROUGH A ROAD DIP, IBC LIFTED AND FELL.  FOLLOWING FALL (WHILE STILL SECURED HORIZONTALLY) LIQUID WAS OBSERVED POURING OUT OF VEHICLE.  AFTER WASHING, VALVE WAS OBSERVED TO BE CRACKED AND SEVERED FROM CONTAINER.  PER DISCUSSION ON/MFG-ALL VALVES ARE BEING UPGRADED TO REMOVE THE FAILED 3 PIECE NIPPLE GASKET VALVE SET.  ON FURTHER REVIEW, ALL OF THIS MODEL IBC WILL BE REMOVED FROM TRANSPORTATION SERVICE DUE TO CONCERNS REGARDING SATISFACTORY VALVE UPGRADE/RE-TEST.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: DRIVER WAS ATTEMPING TO CHECK TRAILER PRIOR TO TAKING IT FROM THE CARRIER'S TERMINAL YARD, AND HE OPENED THE EXTERNAL (HYDROLET) VALVE AND TOOK OFF THE DUST CAP.  PRODUCT THEN POURED FROM THE UNLOADING LINE. DRIVER SHUT OFF WITH THE EMERGENCY SHUTOFF DEVISE ON FRONT FENDER.  ROOT CAUSE OF THE PROBLEM WAS THAT THE TERMINAL VALVE HAD NOT BEEN FULLY CLOSED.  DRIVER ALSO USED IMPROPER METHOD.  HE SHOULD HAVE REMOVED DUST CAP SLOWLY, THEN SLOWLY OPENED EXTERNAL VALVE TO CHECK FOR THE INTERNAL VALVE BEING CLOSED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  THE CARRIER HIRED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND CLEANUP COMPANY TO REMEDIATE THE AREA.

DRIVER WAS DISCONNECTING HOSES AFTER DELIVERY AND PLACING HOSES BACK ON TANK TRUCK, AND PRODUCT DRIPPED INTO DRAIN GRATING IN FRONT OF CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK.  AN OUTSIDE EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY ON RETAINER TO BENJAMIN MOORE & COMPANY WAS PUT TO WORK BY BENJAMIN MOORE & CO TO CLEANUP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  A SECONDARY CONTRACTOR WAS ALSO PUT TO WORK WITH THE POWER EQUIPMENT TO ASSIST THE PRIMARY CLEANUP VENDOR.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

column168: ON 1/29/97, AFTER THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S PLANT, A SAMPLE WAS TAKEN AND THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN THE OK TO UNLOAD.  THE CUSTOMER'S HOSE HAD BEEN HOOKED TO THE FITTING ON THE CARGO TANK.  THE DRIVER PRESSURIZED THE CARGO TANK AND STARTED TO UNLOAD, WHEN HE NOTICED A SMALL DRIP AT THE CONNECTION ON THE CARGO TANK.  DRIVER STARTED TO CHECK THE FITTING AND WHEN HE PLACED HIS HAND ON THE FITTING, THE 2" MALE FITTING BROKE OFF WHERE IT SCREWS INTO THE FOUR BOLT PVC FLANGE ON THE CARGO TANK.  THE CARGO TANK WAS UNDER PRESSURE AND SPRAYED PRODUCT OUT INTO THE UNLOADING SUMP PIT BEFORE THE FLOW COULD BE STOPPED.

column168: THIS TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING WHEN IT CAME OFF OF THE TRAIN. APPX 50 GALLONS OF FLAMMABLE MATERIAL SPILLED FROM A DRUM THAT WAS PUNCTURED ON THE BOTTOM SURFACE.  PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THE GROUND UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER.  REMTECH ENGINEERS FROM MARIETTA, GA WERE BROUGHT IN TO PERFORM THE NECESSARY CLEANUP AND DISPOSE OF THE SPILL RESIDUE.

CRACKED LIQUID PIPE FLANGE, 1/2/97, GATX 25172, PHILADELPHIA DIV, TOWANDA, PA.  AT APPX 1902 HRS, THURSDAY, 1/2/97, A CONRAIL CREW WAS SHIFTING TANK CAR GATX 25172, CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID, SOLUTION AT THE SYLVANIA PLANT IN TOWANDA, PA.  A SYLVANIA EMPLOYEE OBSERVED A VAPOR CLOUD AROUND THE DOME.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM SYLVANIA EXAMINED THE CAR AND UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED A CRACKED LIQUID PIPE FLANGE.  CAR WAS UNLOADED AND REPAIRS WERE MADE BY REPLACING THE LIQUID PIPE FLANGE.

UPON INSPECTION OF CARGO, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING SLIGHTLY FROM THE BUNG AND LID.  LESS THAN 1 GAL OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM DRUM ONTO TRAILER FLOOR WHICH WAS CONTAINED ON STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN.  THE RETAINER RING AND BUNG WERE TIGHTENED AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL PLACED ON PAN.  LOAD PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITHOUT INCIDENT.  DRUM WAS OFFLOADED AND TRAILER FLOOR WAS DECONTAMINATED BY CONSIGNEE.  NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED.

WHILE OFFLOADING MATERIAL, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 2 DRUMS HAD BEEN LEAKING FROM AROUND THE LID.  LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO DEFECTIVE GASKETS.  LESS THAN 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM DRUMS AND WAS CONTAINED INSIDE TRAILER ON STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN.  DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND TRAILER FLOOR DECONTAMINATED BY CONSIGNEE.  NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED.

column168: NO PACKAGING FAILURE ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  VERMONT DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION INCIDENT # WMD 97-023.  OUR DRIVER MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO THE UST'S AT A CONVENIENCE STORE.  THE UST'S ARE EQUIPPED WITH ELECTRONIC SENSORS TO MEASURE VOLUME OF GASOLINE IN TANK.  ICE BUILDUP ON SENSOR CAUSED INACCURATE READING OF GAS IN TANK. RESULTED IN TANK OVERFILL.  GAS CAME OUT AROUND UNUSED REMOTE FILL CAP ON UST.  SPILL CONFINED ON BLACKTOP.  CLEANED UP AND REMOVED THE SAME DAY.

APPX TWO TO THREE GALLONS OF MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE CONCRETE AND GRAVEL OFF-LOADING AREA.  CLEAN UP PERSONNEL WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  ALL POSSIBLY CONTAMINATED GRAVEL/SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND RE-CONTAINERIZED.  THE DAMAGED AREA OF THE ROLL-OFF RECEIVED A TEMPORARY EPOXY PATCH TO SEAL THE PINHOLE.  ADDITIONAL CORRECTIVE MEASURES WILL INCLUDE RE-CONTAINERIZATION OF MATERIAL TO ANOTHER SUITABLE PACKAGE AND ADDITIONAL MECHANICAL REPAIRS WILL BE PERFORMED ON THE ROLL-OFF.

column168: ACCORDING TO ONSITE PERSONNEL, A PETROLEUM TRANSPORT TRUCK OVERTURNED AT THE INTERSECTION OF SIGGLEKOW ROAD AND HWY 51, JUST NORTH OF THE VILLAGE OF MCFARLAND, WISCONSIN AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 AM, JANUARY 22, 1997.  AN ESTIMATED 8900 GALLONS OF GASOLINE PRODUCT SPILLED AS A RESULT OF THE TANKER ROLLOVER.  THE TRUCK CAME TO REST DIRECTLY OVER A STORM SEWER GRATE.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT FLOWED IMMEDIATELY INTO THE STORM SEWER SYSTEM.  THE PRODUCT DID NOT ENTER THE LAKE.  THE VILLAGE OF MCFARLAND FIRST RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ONSITE WITHIN MINUTES OF THE ACCIDENT. SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES WAS CONTACTED TO CONDUCT AN EMERGENCY CLEANUP. SUPERIOR ARRIVED ONSITE AND BEGAN PUMPING UP THE PRODUCT.  THE SEWERS WERE VENTED AND ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE PLACED AT THE SEWER OUTFALLS AND IN THE SPILL PATHWAY.  SAND/BENTONITE DAMS WERE PLACED IN THE DRAINAGE PATH TO STOP THE PRODUCT.

AN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE COMPANY CLEANED UP SPILL AREA.  AFTER A THOROUGH INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ACCIDENT WAS DUE TO INATTENTIVE DRIVING.  DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ABOUT ATTENTIVE DRIVING.  INJURED DRIVERS RETURNED TO THEIR DRIVING DUTIES.  TO DATE, TOTAL COSTS HAVE NOT BEEN DETERMINED.

WEAVER ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP.  THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM, THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED AND ALL CONTAMINATED DEBRIS AND CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE CONSIGNEE. AT APPROXIMATELY 0115 HOURS, MONDAY, JANUARY 13, 1997, IN ELKHART YARD, A CONRAIL TRAINMASTER REPORTED TANK CAR UTLX80638 RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED ANYHYDROUS AMMONIA LEAKING/VENTING FROM THE A-END NEAR HEAD SHIELD. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  CONRAIL EMPLOYEES WERE RELOCATED IN THE ELKHART YARD.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND OPERATIONS IN THAT AREA STOPPED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0745 HOURS, A MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SYSTEMS ARRIVED AT THE SITE WHO EXAMINED THE CAR AND UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED A CRACK APPROXIMATELY 30-36 INCHES IN LENGTH IN THE BASE METAL OF THE A-END HEAD AND EXTENDING BACK THROUGH THE FIRST TRANSITION SECTION OF THE TANK TO A POINT WHERE THE CAR IS WELDED TO THE SADDLE BRACKET/BODY BOLSTER SECTION OF THE TANK CAR.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR WAS COMING FROM THE AREA OF THE CRACK AND THERE WAS A SLIGHT AMMONIA SMELL.  AT APPROX. 1030 HOURS, OH MATERIALS ARRIVED AND APPROX. 1130 HOURS, BP CHEMICAL REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED AT THE SITE.  PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED ON JANUARY 14, 1997.  ARCADIAN MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR RESCAR TO STENCIL THE CAR WITH APPROPRIATE STENCILING FOR A DAMAGED RAIL CAR AND ARRANGED WITH THE FRA TO MOVE THE CAR TO UNION TANK CAR COMPANY.  CAR DEPARTED ON JANUARY 18 AT APPROX. 2130 HOURS.

THIS MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY COVERED WITH ABSORBENTS, THEN REMOVED.  OUR DRIVERS HAVE SINCE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO BE ALERT TO THE POSSIBILITY OF ICE ON MANHOLE COVER GASKET SURFACES.

A PALLET CONTAINING THREE 55 GALLON CONTAINERS OF WASTE SODIUM HYDROXIDE FELL TO THE GROUND SURFACE DURING VEHICLE UNLOADING AT THE SAFETY KLEEN CORP.  MARLBOROUGH FACILITY.  WHILE UNLOADING VEHICLE CONTENTS, THE PALLET SUPPORTING THE CONTAINER FAILED DUE TO THE WEIGHT OF A SECOND PALLET OF WASTE PLACED ON TOP OF THESE DRUMS.  THE WEIGHT CAUSED THE BOTTOM PALLET TO BREAK APART ALLOWING THE DRUMS TO FALL TO THE GROUND AND RUPTURE AT IMPACT.  THE MARLBOROUGH FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND OBSERVED THE INITIAL CONTAINMENT ACTIVITIES. ZECCO INC. WAS MOBILIZED AS THE EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR TO CONTROL AND CONTAINERIZE THE SPILL.  THE FACILITY WILL MOTE VIGOROUSLY INSPECT THE CONDITION OF PALLETS USED TO TRANSPORT WASTE CONTAINERS.  IN ADDITION, IF A SUBSTANTIAL LOAD IS PLACED ABOVE A PALLET OF WASTE CONTAINERS DURING TRANSPORT, THE TOP PALLET OF MATERIAL WILL BE REMOVED WITH A FORK LIFT SEPARATELY.  THE WASTE WAS INADVERTENTLY ADDED TO THE ATTACHED NEW JERSEY MANIFEST (DOCUMENT NO NJA 2641168) THAT WAS BEING USED TO MANAGE THIS SHIPMENT OF WASTE.  THEREFORE, THE MANIFEST INACCURATELY INDICATED THAT SAFETY KLEEN CORP, W BROOKFIELD, MA FACILITY WAS THE GENERATOR OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL RATHER THAN THE SAFETY KLEEN MARLBOROUGH FACILITY.  THE DESIGNATED FACILITY COMPLETED AND UNMANIFESTED WASTE REPORT.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: I WAS TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF 3000 GALLONS OF MINERAL SPIRITS ON JANUARY 22, 1997.  I MADE A PICK-UP OF 2500 GALLONS OF MINERAL SPIRITS.  THE BILL OF LADING WAS SIGNED, TELLING ME THAT THERE WAS PLENTY OF ROOM IN THE TANK, SINCE I HAD ALREADY CUT THE AMOUNT ORDERED BACK BY 500 GALLONS.  I WAS AT TRUCK WHEN I NOTICED THAT THE TANK WAS OVERFLOWING.  I SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND GOT IN TOUCH WITH TOM TAYLOR.  HE HAD ONE OF THE WORKERS BRING OUT A VACUUM AND ABSORBENTS TO TAKE CARE OF THE SPILL.  WHEN THE WORKER WAS CLEANING UP THE SPILL, I WAS ASKING HOW MUCH THE TANK HOLDS AND HOW MANY GALLONS PER FOOT THE TANK HOLDS.  IT WAS AT THAT TIME, HE TOLD ME THAT THEY HAD UP A CHART TELLING WHAT THE TANK CAN HANDLE.  HE ALSO SAID THEY HAD PUT UP THE CHART SINCE THE LAST TIME I MADE A DELIVERY THERE.  THE GROUND WAS FROZEN, SO IT WAS EASY TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  WE ESTIMATED THE SPILL TO BE ABOUT 50 TO 100 GALLONS.  THE REASON THE MINERAL SPIRITS WERE NOT STOPPED IN TIME WAS BECAUSE THERE WAS NO ALARM ON THE TANK.  THE OVERFLOW TANK WAS FULL OF WATER, WHICH WAS FROZEN.  THEREFORE, IT HAD NO PLACE TO GO EXCEPT ON THE GROUND.

BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THE LIQUID LINE VALVE TO BE 1/4 OPEN, AND THE SAFETY CAP WAS NOT LOCKED IN PLACE.  THESE CONDITIONS WERE CORRECTED AND RAIL OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED AFTER THE CAR WAS ISOLATED TO SPUR TRACK (OTHER FREIGHT CARS WERE USED AS A BARRIER DOWNWIND). CRYSTALINE PRODUCT WAS ALSO COVERED TO PREVENT BEING BLOWN OFF OF THE CAR BY THE WIND.  THESE PRECAUTIONS WERE NECESSARY DUE TO THE PRODUCT'S POTENTIAL HEALTH RISKS.  A CONTRACTOR DECONED THE CAR AND THE FOLLOWING CAR, AS WELL AS THE SOIL.  THE SHIPPER WILL RECEIVE A COPY OF THIS REPORT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: AN ODOR WAS DETECTED BY THE CAR INSPECTORS MAKING AN OUTBOUND INSPECTION OF A TRAIN.  BNSF RESPONDERS WERE CALLED TO MAKE AN ASSESSMENT.  THIS RESIDUE SHIPMENT WAS IDENTIFIED.  THE LEAK WAS FOUND TO BE A LOOSE 2" PLUG IN THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  IN ADDITION, THE VALVE HANDLE WAS PINNED IN THE FULLY OPEN POSITION.  BOTH COMPONENTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WILL RECEIVE A COPY OF THIS REPORT.

THE YARD OPERATIONS WERE SUSPENDED FOR TWO HOURS DURING THE ASSESSMENT AND CORRECTIONS.  THE SHIPPER WILL RECEIVE A COPY OF THIS REPORT.  LOSS OF PRODUCTIVITY DUE TO SUSPENSION OF YARD OPERATIONS IN THE VICINITY OF THIS CAR WAS NOT QUALIFIED

VAPOR WAS ESCAPING AT THE MANWAY CLOSURE ACCOUNT AN INADEQUATE SEAL.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR CLASSIFICATION.  THE SHIPPER WILL RECEIVE A COPY OF THIS REPORT.

column168: (A) THIS TANK CAR WAS REPORTED TO BE EMITTING A STRONG ODOR WHEN BEING GIVEN A ROLL-BY INSPECTION OF THE TRAIN.  THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED IN A RELATIVELY NON POPULATED AREA FOUR MILES FROM THE INITIAL REPORT.  BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE RESIDUE SHIPMENT AND FOUND ALL 8 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS TO BE LOOSE.  THE BOLTS WERE FULLY TIGHTENED AND TRAIN WAS RELEASED AFTER CORRECTION OF ANOTHER CAR'S VAPOR RELEASE (GATX 14121).  A COPY OF THIS REPORT WILL BE SENT TO THE SHIPPER.  THE TRAIN DELAY OF 1:15 IS SHOWN IN ITEM 23E COST, AND WAS SPLIT BETWEEN THE TWO RELEASE REPORTS FOR THIS TRAIN. (B) THIS TANK CAR WAS REPORTED TO HAVE A FOUL ODOR WHEN IT RECEIVED A ROLL-BY INSPECTION WHILE IN A TRAIN.  THE TRAIN OPERATED APPROXIMATELY FOUR MILES TO AVOID SOPPING IN A POPULATED AREA.  BNSF RESPONDER ASSESSED THIS RESIDUE SHIPMENT AND FOUND THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE PACKING GLAND NUT TO BE LOOSE.  VAPOR WAS ESCAPING FROM THE PACKING GLAND MATERIAL AND VALVE STEM. THE NUT WAS FULLY TIGHTENED AND THE TRAIN WAS RELEASED AFTER CORRECTION OF ANOTHER CAR'S VAPOR RELEASE (GATX 14128). SEE 97-0130-02.  A COPY OF THIS REPORT WILL BE SENT TO THE SHIPPER.  TRAIN DELAY COST IS SHOWN IN ITEM 23E AND WAS DIVIDED BETWEEN REPORTS.

THIS THREE BAY (OUTLET) HOPPER CAR WAS FOUND TO BE RELEASING PRODUCT WHILE STANDING IN THE TRAINYARD. column168: THE DRIVER DELIVERING TO UNDERGROUND DIESEL TANK.  THE BEGINNING STICK READING INDICATED THE PRODUCT WOULD FIT.  THE PRODUCT CAME OUT OF VAPOR RECOVERY. A DRUM OF A RESIN SOLUTION, A CLASS 3 LIQUID, WAS DAMAGED WHILE BEING LOADED AT PRESTON'S NORTH BILLERICA MASSACHUSETTES TERMINAL.  THE DRUM WAS CHECKED BY A FORK BLADE OPERAOTR.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: A DRUM OF CORROSIVE LIQUID CONTAINING LACTIC ACID, WAS FOUND LEAKING ON ARRIVAL AT PRESTON'S YORK TERMINAL.  A NAIL HAD RUBBED AGAINST THE DRUM RESULTING IN THE LEAK TO FORM.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP, THE DRUM OVER PACKED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

THE EMPLOYEE NOTICED STAINS AND ODOR COMING FROM THIS PACKAGE AND CALLED A DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST TO CHECK THE PACKAGE OUT.  UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE, THE FOLLOWING CONTENTS WERE FOUND.  THERE WERE FOUR PLASTIC BAGS CONTAINING TWO AEROSOL CANS IN EACH BAG.  ONE OF THE CANS IN ONE OF THE TOP HAD COME OFF AND THE AEROSOL TIP HAD OBVIOUSLY BEEN PRESSED AND RELEASED SOME OF THE SPRAY PAINT OUT OF THE CAN.  THE BAGS WITH THE CANS WERE SEPARATED BY SOME PAPER FROM A HOUSING AXLE AND A 2 FAN VAC (WITH SHARP EDGES) IN THE SAME PACKAGE.  WE SUSPECT THAT THE PACKAGING WAS INSUFFICIENT TO KEEP INNER PRODUCTS FROM COMING IN CONTACT WITH EACH OTHER AND ONE OF THE ITEMS HAD KNOCKED THE CAP OFF THE CAN.  THE PAINT WAS ALSO NOT DECLARED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS PRODUCT ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE BY PROPER MARKINGS, LABELS OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION.
THE PLASTIC DRUM WAS FOUND TO HAVE A LOOSE SCREW TOP WHICH WAS NOT SECURED.  THE DRUM WAS HELD FOR INSPECTION AND DISPOSITION FROM THE CUSTOMER.

SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE OCCURRED.  APPARENTLY THE SHIPMENT WAS ON A PALLET AND WAS BEING MOVED BY FORKLIFT WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE OCCURRED.  THE DRIVER APPARENTLY PUT ONE OF THE FORKLIFT BLADES THROUGH THE CONTAINER RESULTING IN ONE OF THE AEROSOLS PUNCTURING AND THE RELEASE OF ABOUT 4 OUNCES OF THE MATERIAL.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED, AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL 3 AEROSOL CANS OF GUN LUBRICANT AS WELL AS SIX PEPPER SPRAY CANNISTERS. THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE INBOUND SORT WHEN LEAKAGE AND FUMES WERE NOTICED COMING FROM THE CONTAINER. UPON RECEIPT OF THE MSDS IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FLASHPOINT OF THE SUBSTANCE WAS SUFFICIENTLY LOW ENOUGH THAT IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN DECLARED AS A REGULATED ITEM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM SORT OPERATION BECAUSE OF APPARENT LEAKAGE, STAIN, AND STRONG ODOR.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND THE SORT WAS EVACUATED BECAUSE OF THE STRONG ODOR.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THERE WERE 3 PEOPLE SENT TO CLINICS FOR SKIN AND INHALATION EXPOSURE.  ALL WERE TREATED AND RELEASED.  THE SHIPPER INDICATED THAT THE INNER CONTAINER WAS A GLASS BOTTLE CONTAINING 3 LITERS OF THE MATERIAL.  THE PACKAGE INSTRUCTION ONLY ALLOWS 2.5 LITERS WHICH MAY HAVE CAUSED THE BOTTLE INSIDE TO BREAK.  THE INCIDENT AND THE DISCREPANCY WERE REPORTED TO SPECIAL AGENT JIM STILLWELL OF THE FAA.  THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS HELD FOR DISPOSAL BY A WASTE COMPANY.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED INBOUND WHEN ODOR AND LEAKAGE WERE NOTICED COMING FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED, OPENED, AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL AN AUTOMOBILE ENGINE CARBURETOR.  THIS UNIT HAD NOT BEEN COMPLETELY DRAINED OF FUEL BEFORE IT WAS SHIPPED.  UPON ARRIVAL AT DFW, THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE ATTENTION OF THE DANGEROUS GOODS AGENT, DANNY MITCHELL, WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE CORPORATE DANGEROUS GOODS DUTY OFFICER WHO IT TURN NOTIFIED THE FAA'S DUTY OFFICER, ALTHEA MACK. UNFORTUNATELY DURING THE COURSE OF THESE NOTIFICATIONS, THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT SECURED IN THE USUAL LOCATION.  CONSEQUENTLY, THE PACKAGE WAS RESEALED AND INADVERTENTLY PLACED ON A VEHICLE FOR TRANSPORTATION TO AUSTIN, TX WHICH WAS THE FINAL DESTINATION FOR THE SHIPMENT.  EFFORTS TO CATCH THE SHIPMENT BEFORE IT WAS PROCESSED AND DELIVERED TO THE RECIPIENT WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  THIS SEQUENCE OF EVENTS WAS REPORTED TO SPECIAL AGENT ALTHEA MACK AS WELL AS SPECIAL AGENT STEPHEN PEREZ OF THE DFW/CAFSO OF THE FAA.

THE PITTED SEATING SURFACE ON BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE, CELX 1033, JANUARY 20,1997, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 HOURS, MONDAY, JANUARY 20, 1997, A GATX TERMINAL MANAGER DISCOVERED TANK CAR CELX 1033 CONTAINING HEPTANOIC ACID LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE INSIDE GATX TERMINAL LEASED BY HOECHST CELANESE CORPORATION.  AN APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1330 HOURS, AN ENVIRONMENTAL SPILL CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND MINIMIZED THE LEAK.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS ON JANUARY 21, 1997, THE CAR WAS OFF LOADED INTO TWO TANK TRUCKS.  THE TANK CAR WAS RETURNED TO BAY CITY FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  UPON EXAMINING THE CAR, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SEATING SURFACE PITTED ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE.  THE CAR WAS SENT TO A SHOP FOR REPAIR.

column168: THIS OCCURED DURING A TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM RAILCAR ACFX 94783 INTO FLEET TRANSPORT TRAILER 851080.  THE FLEET TRANSPORT LOADER EMPLOYEE HAD FAILED TO CLOSE THE OUTLET VALVE ON THE CARGO TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT RAN OUT UNTIL HE SAW IT AND SHUT DOWN LOADING AND THEN CLOSED TRAILER OUTLET. THIS EMPLOYEE FAILED TO REPORT THE SPILL, AND IT WAS DISCOVERED 2 DAYS LATER BY THE FACILITY SHOP FOREMAN.  A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR, FERGUSON HARBOR, WAS HIRED TO TREAT AND CLEAN UP.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  THIS WAS REPORTED TO NRC 373721, AND TO GEORGIA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES EP DIVISION 012197-04.  THE LOADER EMPLOYEE HAS BEEN DISCHARGED FROM EMPLOYMENT.

THE DOCK MAN WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING DRUM FROM ONE TRAILER TO ANOTHER. THE DRUM WAS LAID ON ITS SIDE AND TAKEN TO OS&D WHERE IT WAS PUT UPSIDE-DOWN IN A POLY OVERPACK DRUM TO AWAIT FURTHER HANDLING. ON JM 3RD WHILE DOING A CLEAN UP ON TRANSFORMER VAULT #803 AT STORY AND ROSDALE AVE IN THE BRONX. A SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE OFF SHIFT DUTY SUPERVISOR AT ASTORIA TRANSPORTATION.  APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF PCB CONTAMINTED WATER LEAKED FROM A SMALL SPILL IN THE FILL PIPE OF TANKER #80070 .  LIL #43790A.  THE TANKER IN QUESTION WAS DRAINED OFF INTO A VACCUM TANKER ON LOCATION, THE LEAKING PIPE SECURED AND THE SPILL FROM THE TANKER WAS CLEANED UP WITHIN 1 HOUR.  THE CLEANUP ON THE VAULT CONTINUED AND WAS COMPLETED.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: ONE JANUARY 16, 1997, AT APPROXIMATELY 1240 HURS, RAILROAD TANK CAR NATX 30694, LOAD OF PETROLEUM DISTILLATE, N.O.S. (HEXENE), WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS'S BATON ROUGE, LOUISANA RAILYARD.  THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING ONLY WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED. THEREFORE, THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE LEAKAGE.  THE CONSIGNEE, EXXON CHEMICAL AMERICAS, CONTACT NAME MR. WILLARD BEARD, WAS NOTIFIED AND A RESPONSE CREW ARRIVED ON-SITE AT 1330 HOURS THE SAME DAY.  THE EXXON RESPONSE CREW INDICATED THAT THEY FOUND A BAD DOME LID GASKET AND REPLACED IT WITH A NEW GASKET. EXXON CREW ALSO INDICATED THAT THE TANK CAR WAS OVER-LOADED AND ARRANGED TO HAVE 1,000 GALLONS OF MATERIAL REMOVED FROM THE CAR.  ALL REPAIRS AND TRANSFERS WERE COMPLETED AT 1745 HOURS ON THAT SAME DAY.  THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

DURING THE SORT THE BOX WAS TIPPED OVER, IMMEDIATELY LIQUID NITROGEN WAS SEEN FLOWING OUT OF THE BOX, NOT JUST VAPORS, BUT THE ACTUAL LIQUID ITSELF.  THE BOX WAS RIGHTED AND THE LEAKAGE CEASED. I CALLED THE SHIPPER AND SPOKE TO DOTTIE DIMAGIBA DURING MY TELEPHONIC INTERVIEW SHE FAILED TO TELL ME (ONLY AFTER I PROMPTED HER) THAT SHE IN FACT POURED OUT ALL OF THE RESIDUAL LIQUID, BASED ON THE AMOUNT SPILLED I BELIEVED THAT SHE FAILED TO ADEQUATELY ENSURE THAT ALL REMAINING LIQUID WAS POURED OFF, IF ANY HAVE BEEN POURED OFF IN THE FIRST PLACED, BOTH D.O.T. AND ISAO HAVE DE-REGULATED DRY DEWARS,  HOWEVER, IF ANY STANDING LIQUID NITROGEN IS PRESENT IN THE DEWARS.  THE DEWARS BECOME REGULATED UNDER UN1977.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO JIM WISEMAN.  JIM ASKED THAT WE HOLD THE FREIGHT PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATE

RESPONDED TO SPILL, RESTRICTED AREA, PUT ON PPE.  DETERMINED PACKAGE TO BE HAZARDOUS 8 CORROSIVE.  FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET TO CLEAN UP SPILL, PROCESSED PACKAGE THROUGH DMP AND DECONTAMINATED.

MATERIAL WAS LOADED ON A PALLET CAPPED WITH PLYWOOD WITH BANDING AROUND CONTAINERS. THE BAND AROUND THE CONTAINERS FAILED CAUSING THE CONTAINER TO BECOME LOOSE AND THEY FELL OFF THE TRUCK.  THE CONTAINERS FELL IN THE ROADWAY AND WE LATER STRUCK BY A CAR.  THE CONTAINERS WERE CRUSHED BY THE IMPACT OF THE CAR.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF PACKAGE FAILURE OR BEING A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SHIPPER HAD CHANGED PROCEDURES AND NOW SHRINK WRAP IN ADDITION TO BANDING THE MATERIAL TO THE PALLET WHICH WOULD PREVENT A RECURRENCE.

ON THURSDAY, JANUARY 23, 1997, AT 3:15PM, APPROXIMATELY 50-GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND OUT OF THE TOP OF A COVERED TOLL-OFF BOX AS THE ROLL-OFF BOX WAS BEING HYDRAULICALLY LOADED ONTO A ROLL-OFF FRAME.  FREE LIQUID IN THE BOX CAME FROM PREVIOUSLY FROZEN RAINWATER CAPTURED UNDERNEATH THE LINER IN THE BOX.  FREE LIQUID WAS NOT OBSERVED IN THE BOX AT THE TIME OF PICK UP.  THE BOX WAS UPRIGHT WHICH STOPPED THE LIBERATION OF ANY MATERIAL.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED BY DIKING THE AREA AND CAPTURING FREE LIQUID WITH AN ABSORBENT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS REMOVED USING A BACKHOE AND PLACED INTO A PROPERLY LABELED DOT SHIPPING CONTAINER.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER 374097.

column62: Derailment; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: (A) A BNSF TRAIN (OPERATING ON V. P. OWNED AND MAINTAINED TRACKS) DERAILED THIRTEEN CARS ACCOUNT A BROKEN RAIL THAT APPARENTLY FAILED AS THE TRAIN PASSED OVER IT.  THREE OF EIGHT TANK CARS TRANSPORTING SODIUM HYDROXIDE RELEASED PRODUCT.  A TOTAL OF FOUR PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED DURING THE ASSESSMENT.  THIS CAR RELEASED PRODUCT ACCOUNT THE TOP VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE SHEARED OFF IN THE DERAILMENT.  ALL PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. ENVIRONMENTAL CONSIDERATIONS INVOLVED USING ACIDS TO NEUTRALIZE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND WATER.  REMEDIATION IS COMPLETE; HOWEVER, MONITORING CONTINUES.  REFERENCE BNSF TRAIN ACCIDENT REPORT TX-0197-102. (B) A BNSF TRAIN (OPERATING ON V. P. OWNED AND MAINTAINED TRACK) DERAILED THIRTEEN CARS ACCOUNT A BROKEN RAIL THAT APPARENTLY FAILED AS THE TRAIN PASSED OVER IT.  THREE OF EIGHT TANK CARS TRANSPORTING SODIUM HYDROXIDE RELEASED PRODUCT.  A TOTAL OF FOUR PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED DURING THE ASSESSMENT. THIS CAR RELEASED PRODUCT ACCOUNT HOLES IN THE UPPER ENDS OF THE CAR.  THE APPLEBY FIRE DEPT PLUGGED THESE HOLES AND STOPPED THE RELEASE.  APPX 500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  ENVIRONMENTAL CONSIDERATIONS INVOLVED USING ACIDS TO NEUTRALIZE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND WATER.  REMEDIATION IS COMPLETE, BUT MONITORING CONTINUES.  BNSF TRAIN ACCIDENT REPORT IS TX-0197-102. (C) A BNSF TRAIN (OPERATING ON V.P. OWNED AND MAINTAINED TRACKS) DERAILED THIRTEEN CARS ACCOUNT A BROKEN RAIL THAT APPARENTLY FAILED AS THE TRAIN PASSED OVER IT. THREE OF EIGHT TANK CARS TRANSPORTING SODIUM HYDROXIDE RELEASED PRODUCT. A TOTAL OF FOUR PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED DURING THE ASSESSMENT. THIS CAR RELEASED PRODUCT ACCOUNT THE TOP VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE SHEARED OFF IN THE DERAILMENT. APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF OF THE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. ENVIRONMENTAL CONSIDERATIONS INVOLVED USING ACIDS TO NEUTRALIZE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND WATER. REMEDIATION IS COMPLETE; HOWEVER, MONITORING CONTINUES. REFERENCE BNSF TRAIN ACCIDENT REPORT TX-0197-102.

column168: BAY WEST WAS CONTACTED BY MR JOHN BUCCIARELLI, OLIN CORP, TO RESPOND TO AN UNKNOWN LEAKING CONTAINER FOUND IN A TRANSCONTINENTAL REFRIGERATION LINES TRAILER AT DUFOUR SALES LOCATED AT 304 W 61ST ST, MINNEAPOLIS, MN.  BAY WEST DISPATCHED FOUR RESPONSE PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT TO ASSESS THE SITUATION, CONTAINERIZE THE LEAKING DRUM, AND COLLECT AND CONTAINERIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  UPON ARRIVAL, BAY WEST MET WITH MR ULEY SEAL, MINN FIRE DEPT, MR KEVIN FAUS AND MR MARK OEMICHEN, BOTH OF MINN POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY (MCPA), MR PETE MARCOTTE, MINN DEPT OF TRANSPORTATION (MN/DOT), AND MR ROGER VAN TASSEL, CITY OF MINN, AND ASSESSED THE SITUATION.  IT IS OUR UNDERSTANDING THAT APPX 50 GALLONS OF HYDROFLUORIC ACID WAS SPILLED FROM A 55 GAL CONTAINER. ************** BAY WEST DONNED LEVEL B PERSONNEL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE) TO CONDUCT AIR MONITORING IN THE SUBJECT TRAILER.  DRAGER TUBES, WHICH INDICATE LEVELS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND HYDROFLUORIC ACID, WERE USED TO DETERMINE POSSIBLE EXPOSURE LEVELS.  BAY WEST FOUND 3 PARTS PER MILLION (PPM) OF HYDROFLUORIC ACID AND 4 PPM OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  A DRAGER TUBE FOR AMMONIA WAS USED AND NO AMMONIA WAS FOUND IN THE TRAILER.  DURING THE ASSESSMENT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE DRUM AT THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER WAS DAMAGED AND EMPTY.  A POSITIVE IDENTIFICATION COULD NOT BE MADE AS TO WHAT WAS SPILLED FROM THE DRUM DUE TO THE POSITION OF THE CONTAINER.  ***************** BAY WEST UNLOADED THE TRAILER IN THE DUFOUR SALES WAREHOUSE AND DETERMINED THE DRUM CONTAINED HYDROFLUORIC ACID.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVER-PACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED POLYETHYLENE CONTAINER AND LABELED.  USING SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL, BAY WEST BEGAN TO RECOVER AS MUCH OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL AS POSSIBLE.  APPX ONE QUART OF FREE LIQUID REMAINED IN THE TRAILER UNDER THE FLOORING.  CONTAMINATED PALLETS AND DEBRIS WERE CUT INTO PIECES AND PLACED INTO POLYETHYLENE DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  THE TRAILER BED WAS DAMAGED BY THE HYDROFLUORIC ACID.  USING A NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION, BAY WEST WASHED THE TRUCK BED AND THE DOCK AREA.  ADDITIONAL SODA ASH WAS PLACED ON THE TRUCK BED FLOOR TO NEUTRALIZE ANY HYDROFLUORIC ACID THAT MAY HAVE BEEN REACTING WITH THE TRUCK BED INSULATION.  ********************* BAY WEST RETURNED TO THE SITE ON 1/31/97 TO PREPARE THE DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  ONE DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE EXPANDING, AND BAY WEST RELIEVED THE PRESSURE WITH A REMOTE DRUM PUNCH.  ADDITIONAL SODA ASH WAS ADDED TO THE MATERIAL BEFORE REPACKAGING.  NINE DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE GENERATED DURING THE SPILL RESPONSE.  BAY WEST AND OLIN CORP COORDINATED THE DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE.  ALL DISPOSAL RECORDS WILL BE SUBMITTED TO OLIN CORP UPON RECEPIT.  BAY WEST RECOMMENDS THAT A COPY OF THIS REPORT BE SUBMITTED TO THE REGULATING AUTHORITIES THAT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THANK YOU FOR THE OPPORTUNITY TO PROVIDE YOU WITH EMERGENCY RESPONSE SERVICES. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS CONCERNING THIS REPORT, PLEASE CALL ME AT 291-3470.  MARK SCONAGLIA, CHMM, REP, EM

PACKAGE TRAVELED THROUGH THE CONVEYOR SYSTEM FROM THE UNLOAD AREA TO THE LOADING AREA (PD2).  DAMAGE CAN EASILY OCCUR WHILE PACKAGES ARE TRAVELING ON THE CONVEYOR SYSTEM.  THE DAMAGE WOULD GO UNDETECTED FROM THE PRIMARY SORT TO THE LOADING AREA IN MOST CASES, AS NO ONE WILL SEE OR TOUCH THE PACKAGE UNTIL IT REACHES A "PICKOFF" AREA FOR A PARTICULAR WORK AREA.  THE BEST WAY WE HAVE DISCOVERED SO FAR, TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IS TO PLACE THE 5 PART LABEL PACKAGES ON THE "IRREG TRAINS" AS THEY COME OUT OF THE UNLOAD AREA.  THEY ARE THEN ESSENTIALLY "HAND CARRIED" FROM THAT POINT TO THEIR DESTINAION TRAILER.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS, SUNDAY, JUNE 26, 1997 FLATCAR RTTX 972313 CONTAINING TWO - TWENTY FOOT CONTAINER PLACARDED RADIOACTIVE WAS DISCOVERED BY EMPLOYEES AT THE CONRAIL ALLENTOWN RAIL YARD WITH ONE OF THE CONTAINER DOORS BROKEN PARTIALLY OPEN. FLATCAR HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN A SWITCHING OPERATION THAT CAUSED THE CONTENTS OF CONTAINER AR-55 TO SHIFT AGAINST THE CONTAINER DOORS. ** APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE AND SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION BY A CONRAIL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FIELD SERVICE MANAGER REVEALED THAT THE RIGHT SIDE CONTAINER DOOR HAD OPENED APPROXIMATELY TWO FEET DUE TO THE SHIFTING ON THE LOAD (TURBINE PARTS) AGAINST THE DOOR. THE CONTAMINATED MACHINERY PARTS WERE UNROUTE FOR DESTRUCTION AT THE TIME OF THE OCCURRENCE. ** AN AIR QUALITY SPECIALIST FROM THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION RESPONDED TO THE SITE AS DID REPRESENTATIVES FROM PECO CONTAMINTES HAD BEEN RELEASE FROM THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED WITH PLASTIC AND LOAD SUBSEQUENTLY READJUSTED AND SECURED BY AN APPROVED ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR. UPON COMPLETION OF REPAIRS, THE FLATCAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

DURING THE RELOAD OPERATION LAST NIGHT WE FOUND A BOX THAT WAS EMITTING A STRONG ALCOHOL-BASED ODOR.  THE BOXES OUTER MARKING REFLECTED THOSE OF A WHISKEY COMPANY. THE BOX WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THIS MORNING AS WE WERE PROCESSING THE BOX TO BE RETURNED, IT WAS OPENED .  AT THAT POINT IT WAS REALIZED THAT THE ORIGIN OF THE ALCOHOL ODOR WAS ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL, RATHER THAN ALCOHOL DESIGNED FOR CONSUMPTION.  UPON BEING NOTIFIED BY THE AMARILLO FEDEX STATION, I CALLED FAA SPECIAL AGENT ALTHEA MACK FROM DFW CASFO.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING , SHIPPING PAPERS, NOR OTHER INDICATOR THAT WOULD HAVE ALLOWED US TO READILY IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS AS BEING REGULATED.  THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED.  I SPOKE TO MR. RICKY WATSON.

column168: AT ABOUT 12:00 P.M. ON FRIDAY, JANUARY 10, 1997, APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF UNLEADED (PLUS) GASOLINE WERE INCIDENTALLY RELEASED AT JETT SHELL #479 WHICH IS LOCATED ON HWY 60 (VERSAILLES RD.) APPROXIMATELY 1/4 MILE WEST OF THE HWY 60 & INTERSTATE 64 INTERCHANGE. THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHILE NEWCOMB OIL CO. TRANSPORT DRIVER BRUCE CLEMENTS WAS ATTEMPTING TO FILL THE STORE'S PLUS UNLEADED UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. THE SPILL OCCURRED WHEN THE FITTING ON THE DELIVERY HOSE BECAME UNATTACHED FROM THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK'S FLAPPER-VALVE OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICE AND 2 INADEQUATE ATTACHMENT OF THE DELIVERY HOSE FITTING TO THE DROP TUBE BY THE DRIVER. THE DRIVER CLOSED THE TRANSPORT TANK'S VALVE WHICH SUPPLIED THE DELIVERY HOSE UPON NOTICING THE PROBLEM, BUT A DELAY OCCURRED BETWEEN THE TIME THAT THE SPILL STARTED AND THE TIME THAT THE SPILL WAS NOTICED. THIS DELAY (OF AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF TIME) ATTRIBUTED TO THE LARGE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BEING RELEASED. THE SPILLED PRODUCT FLOWED DIRECTLY DOWN-GRADIENT FROM THE SPILL POINT, ACROSS THE DIRVEWAY AND TOWARD A STORM WATER DRAIN (SEE FIGURE 1 AND ATTACHMENT A). THE DRIVER QUICKLY APPLIED ALL OF THE ABSORBENT PADS THAT WERE CARRIED ON HIS TRUCK TO THE SPILL. THE DRIVER THEN ALERTED THE STORE'S MANAGER TO CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE MANAGER AND DRIVER APPLIED ALL OF THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL (OIL-DRY) FROM THE STORE TO THE SPILL. ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE OBTAINED  FROM ANOTHER NEWCOMB OIL CO. C-STORE LOCATION IN FRANKFORT AND APPLIED TO SPILL.THE FRANKLIN CO. FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 12:11 P.M. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL COMMUNICATED WITH STATE ENVIRONMENTAL AGENCIES.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TOOK NO FURTHER KNOWN ACTION AND DEPARTED FROM THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 12:50 P.M. THE FRANKLIN CO. FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED  ON THE SCENE AT 12:11 P.M. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL COMMUNICATED WITH STATE ENVIRONMENTAL AGENCIES. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TOOK NO FURTHER KNOWN ACTION AND DEPARTED FROM THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 12:50 P.M. THE NEWCOMB OIL CO OFFICE IN BARDSTOWN, KY WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL BY BRUCE CLEMENTS BETWEEN 12:00  P.M. EMERGENCY RESPONSE EMPLOYEES FROM NEWCOMB OIL CO. RESPONDED FROM LOUISVILLE AND FROM BARDSTOWN WITH ADDITIONAL SPILL CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN-UP SUPPLIES. THE ADDITIONAL SUPPLIES AND THE BULK OF THE ADDITIONAL MANPOWER ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 P.M. THE KY NATURAL RESOURCES EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER AND THE NATIONAL SPILL RESPONSE CENTER WERE NOTIFIED BETWEEN 1:00 P.M. AND 1:15 P.M. ON FRIDAY, JANUARY 10, 1997. THE ORIGINAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT WAS BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN SPILLED AT THAT TIME WAS 25-30 GALLONS. (UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE AND SURVEY OF THE SPILL AREA, THE AMOUNT WAS UPDATED TO APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS. UPON A WEEKEND REVIEW OF THE LOAD CHARTS OF THE TRUCK FROM WHICH THE SPOIL ORIGINATED, THE DISPATCHER FROM NEWCOMB OIL CO. DETERMINED THAT BETWEEN 400 AND 500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED. THE KY NATURAL RESOURCES AND ENVIRON

AT 1030 HRS. ON 010297, MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY M.T.O. BILL BRUNSKILL AT GREEN RIVER WYOMING THAT TANK CAR UTLX99018 WAS REPORTED LEAKING IN THE ROCK SPRINGS YARD.  AN INSPECTION OF THE CAR WAS CONDUCTED UPON ARRIVAL AND THE CAR WAS FOUND TO HAVE A SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  MGR. RODABOUGH ATTEMPTED TO CHOKE THE VALVE, WITHOUT SUCCESS.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE CAR WAS DESTINED TO S.F. PHOSPHATE, WHICH IS LOCATED SIX MILES FROM THE LOCATION OF THE CAR. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO MOVE THE CAR TO DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING.  THIS MOVE AND THE UNLOADING OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED AT 1700 HRS. ON 010397.

ON 01/03/97 GATX TANK CAR REPAIR SHOP AT COLTON, CALIFORNIA REMOVED THE RESIDUE FROM THIS CAR AND APPLIED A PATCH TO THE "A" END OF THE CAR.  CAR WAS RELEASED FROM CALIFORNIA STEEL AT FONTANA, CA., AFTER REPAIRS FOR MOVEMENT ONTO GATS SHOPS AT COLTON CALIFORNIA.  ON 01/04/97, THIS CAR ARRIVED IN SP/UP YARD AT COLTON, CALIFORNIA AND WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THE PATCH WHICH HAD BEEN APPLIED THE DAY BEFORE.  GATX REPATCHED THE CAR AND A SPECIAL MOVE WAS MADE TO MOVE THE CAR INTO THE GATX SHOP AT COLTON. LEAKAGE APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN FROM PRODUCT TRAPPED WITHIN THE LINER.

AT 0930 HRS. ON MONDAY THE 6TH OF JANUARY, MR. JOHNLYON M.T.O. AT OGDEN UT. CALLED TO REPORT A LEAKING TANKER.  HE INDICATED THAT TANK CAR UTLX12719 WAS LEAKING PROFUSELY FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE UPFE SPILL PAD AT RIVER DALE.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT A TWO INCH HOLE HAD BEEN PUNCHED THROUGH THE BOTTOM OF THE SUMP.  THE PUNCHED OUT COUPON WAS STILL ATTACHED TO THE BOTTOM OF THE SUMP, WITH PRODUCT FLOWING THROUGH THE HOLE, ONTO THE CATCH BASIN, AND INTO THE DRAINS GOING TO THE OIL SEPARATOR.  A LARGE HOLE WAS EXCAVATED TO ACCOMODATE THE DOME ASSEMBLY, AND THE CAR WAS DERAILED INTO ITS TOP.  THE BOTTOM STOPPED LEAKING AND THE TOP STARTED.  ALL THE ACID FROM THE SAFETY VENT WAS CONTAINED IN THE HOLE THAT HAD BEEN PREPARED FOR THE DOME ASSEMBLY.  THE PUNCHED OUT COUPON WAS POUNDED BACK INTO PLACE AND WELDED. THE CAR WAS ROLLED BACK TO THE UPRIGHT POSITION AND ALL LEAKING CEASED.  A TOTAL OF 10450 GALLONS WAS REMOVED BY TRUCK.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT THERE WAS A TOTAL LOSS OF ACID OF APPROXIMATELY 2500 GALLONS.

AT 0930 HRS. ON MONDAY THE 13TH DAY OF JANUARY, MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM MR. TERRY LANGSTON THE WATER TREATMENT OPERATOR AT THE ROPER YARD, THAT THERE WAS A TANK CAR IN THE YARD THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM A SERIES OF APPLIANCES THAT HAD BEEN APPLIED TO THE CAR FOR LOADING AND UNLOADING. MR. RODABOUGH RELEASED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR, WHICH QUELLED THE LEAK, THEN REMOVED THE UNLOADING APPARATUS AND REPLACED IT WITH THE BLIND FLANGE WHICH WAS STILL ATTACHED TO THE CAR BY A CHAIN.  THE SPILL AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED WITH THE USE OF ONE HUNDRED POUNDS OF SODIUM BICARBONATE. THE UNLOADING APPARATUS WAS RETURNED TO DYCE CHEMICAL AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CAR RETURNED AS WELL.

column168: ON 2/2/97 A REQUEST FROM HAZ MAT COORDINATOR TONY FRY TO CHECK OUT A POSSIBLE LEAKING SHIPMENT WITH A GASOLINE ODOR WAS MADE.  THE LOCATION OF THE SHIPMENT WAS ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  HAZ MAT COORDINATOR, ADDIE CAMPTON RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL I OBSERVED A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX SECURED TO AN ALUMINUM PALLET WITH METAL BANDING AND SCREWS.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED WITH BOLD BLACK LETTERING ON ONE SIDE AS FOLLOWS: DISH BARRELL BOX.  ORIENTATION ARROWS THAT WERE RUNNING HORIZONTALLY ON THE BOX.  THE BOX WAS WRAPPED AROUND AND SECURED TO PALLET AND CONTAINED NO FIBERBOARD BOTTOM.  THE INNER BOX CONTAINED A 1966 SUZUKI SS MODEL M31 MOTOR CYCLE, ALSO PACKAGED WITH THE CYCLE WAS A BOX CONTAINING: A REGISTRATION CERTIFICATE, CERTIFICATE OF TITLE, LICENSE PLATE, BILL OF SALE, SET OF KEYS, OWNER'S MANUAL AND A BOX CONTAINING MISCELLANEOUS MOTORCYCLE PARTS.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE FUEL TANK FOR THE MOTORCYCLE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CLOSURE WAS LOOSE CAUSING THE SPILL. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZ MAT CERTIFICATIONS TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  UNDECLARED SHIPMENT.

ALSO, SUGGESTED THAT NO HAZ MAT BE PLACED ON THE FLOOR, FROM NOW ON THEY WILL BE PLACED ON PALLETS OR A BUGGY.

HE THEN RESECURED THE MANWAY.  TOM WARNOCK, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AND HE ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 51310, DATED 1/27/97.  FRANK VIDALIN, MGR TRANS REGS, AGRIUM INC., CALGARY, CANADA, WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED A COPY OF THIS REPORT FOR HANDLING WITH THEIR AGENT, CONDA PHOSPHATE OPERATIONS.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPX 0250 HRS 012997, SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE UNION PACIFIC RAIL YARD AT COUNCIL BLUFFS, IOWA, RESULTED IN A COLLISION BETWEEN TANK CAR CRGX 30052, DENATURED ALCOHOL, AND TANK CAR GATX 55997, ANHYDROUS AMMONIA (RESIDUE).  INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO UPRR SPECIAL AGENT K C DECHANT AND AN INSPECTION REQUESTED.  UPON ARRIVAL AT 0400 HRS, DECHANT NOTED A LARGE POOL OF LIQUID ALONG SIDE THE TANK CARS AND SUBSEQUENTLY FOUND THAT A COUPLER BYPASS HAD RESULTED IN A PUNCTURE OF THE TANK HEAD ON CAR CRGX 30052.  THE NATURE OF THE PUNCTURE AND POOLING OF PRODUCT AROUND THE POINT OF IMPACT PRECLUDED ANY ATTEMPT TO REDUCE OR STOP THE LEAK.  LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT, AND A SUBSEQUENT SITE SURVEY BY DECHANT AND FIRE OFFICIALS AT 0420 HRS DISCLOSED ALL CONTENTS HAD LEAKED FROM THE TANK CAR.  THE RESULTING SPILL WAS CONFINED BY TOPOGRAPHY TO A POOL RANGING FROM 10 TO 40 FT IN WIDTH, 250 FT LONG.  AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WAS 17 DEG. F., BELOW THE FLASH POINT OF THE PRODUCT (55 DEG.F. AS VERIFIED BY THE SHIPPER); HOWEVER, VAPORS WERE NOTICEABLY EMITTED, AND A FOAM BLANKET WAS SUBSEQUENTLY APPLIED OVER THE POOL TO REDUCE THE VOLUME OF VAPOR EXPECTED TO MOVE INTO SURROUNDING AREAS.  ******************* LIQUID WAS SIPHONED INTO TANK TRUCKS AND TAKEN OFF SITE BY A PRIVATE CONTRACTOR FOR STORAGE AND DISPOSAL.  THE VOLUME OF MATERIAL SPILLED IS ESTIMATED, BY WEIGHT, AS 28800 GALS, WITH APPX 6000-8000 GALS OF WATER USED IN THE FOAMING OPERATION.  CLEANUP OPERATIONS RESULTED IN THE RECOVERY OF 33000 GALS OF LIQUID, INCLUDING BOTH ALCOHOL AND WATER.  ONCE LIQUID WAS RECOVERED, THE SPILL SITE WAS COVERED WITH SAND AS A PROTECTIVE MEASURE DURING RERAILING OPERATIONS.  FURTHER REMEDIATION OF THE SITE IS IN PROGRESS, UNDER APPROVAL OF THE IOWA DEPT OF NATURAL RESOURCES.

AT 12:50HRS ON 01/11/97, CTS MANAGER LERCH WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED BY CAR DEPARTMENT THAT LOADED TANK CAR UTLX 201073, LOCATED ON FORWARDER YARD TRACK 10 WAS LEAKING.  ON ARRIVAL, MANAGER LERCH NOTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT A RATE OF LESS THAN 1 GALLON AN HOUR AND PLACED A BUCKET UNDER CAR TO CONTAIN LEAK.  INSPECTION OF CAR REVEALED 8 BOLTS WHICH SECURE THE 4 INCH BOTTOM OUTLET BALL VALVE WERE LOOSE, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE.  AFTER TIGHTENING THE 8 BOLTS APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TO 3/4 TURN EACH, LERCH WAS ABLE TO STOP RELEASE OF PRODUCT AND SECURE CAR.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAIN OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED AS A RESULT OF THIS RELEASE.  THERE WAS NO CLEAN UP SPILL DUE TO EVAPORIZATION OF PRODUCT.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, VERN LIBBY WAS NOTIFIED BY KEN KUBIC, MYO, FIFE, WA, THAT HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY BRAD CADY, TERMINAL MANAGER RAIL HANDLING INC., TACOMA, WA.  HE ADVISED THAT UTLX 11227 HAD BEEN SPOTTED AT HIS FACILITY FOR UNLOADING AND WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT OUT THE SIDE AND ONTO THE CEMENT UNLOADING PLATFORM.  MR. CADY ADVISED SAHM LIBBY THAT A SAND DIKE HAD BEEN PLACED AROUND THE POOLING ACID, DIRECTING IT INTO A DRAIN EMPTYING INTO A CONTAINMENT TANK.  HE FURTHER ADVISED THAT THEY WOULD ATTEMPT TO PLUG THE HOLE.  UPON ARRIVAL, LIBBY WAS INFORMED BY CADY THAT THEY WERE UNABLE TO PLUG THE HOLE, HOWEVER; THEY HAD RELIEVED THE PRESSURE FROM BEHIND THE LEAK, AND HAD MADE THE HOLE LARGER.  A PLASTIC OPEN HEAD DRUM WAS PLACED UNDER THE TANK CAR TO COLLECT THE ACID RUNNING DOWN AND AROUND THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR.  A WOODEN PLUG HAD ALSO BEEN PLACED IN THE HOLE.  CADY HAD CONTRACTED WITH BULK SERVICES TRANSPORT, TACOMA, WA, TO TRANSLOAD THE TANK CAR INTO TRUCK TRAILER, IN ORDER TO UNLOAD THE TANK CAR AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE.  THE HOLE IN THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TANK CAR WAS ESTIMATED TO BE 3/8" IN DIAMETER 15'6" FROM THE A END AND 4'10" UP FROM THE BOTTOM CENTER OF THE TANK CAR.  CADY ESTIMATED 50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST AND HE ADVISED THAT THE TANK CAR WAS UNLOADED AT 1880 HRS. ON 1/16/97.  SAHM LIBBY AND CADY SPOKE WITH REGIONAL MANAGER CTS, DEAN WHITELEY, WHO INSTRUCTED CADY TO STENCIL THE TANK CAR "LEAKY TANK CAR, DO NOT RELOAD UNTIL REPAIRED".  HE WAS ALSO INSTRUCTED TO MARK THE LOCATION OF THE HOLE WITH AN "X".  CADY INDICTED THAT HE WAS STILL WAITING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE TANK CAR OWNER AS TO THE FINAL DISPOSITION OF THE INCIDENT.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT JONES RESPONDED TO REPORT OF TANKCAR DMIX 300078 LEAKING LIQUID FROM TOP OF TANKCAR.  SAHM JONES INSPECTED TANKCAR, AND FOUND THAT ONE OF THE THREE PLUGS ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING HAD BEEN LEFT OUT, WHICH WOULD ALLOW LIQUID TO SPLASH OUT DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  SAHM JONES REPLACED PLUG, AND NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF FINDINGS.

UNION PACIFIC EMPLOYEES AT SIOUX CITY, IA OBSERVED LIQUID RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF TANKCAR UTLX 20033 IN THE UPRR RAILYARD.  IT COULD NOT BE READILY DETERMINED IF THE LIQUID WAS PRODUCT FROM THE CAR, OR THE RESULT OF SNOWMELT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  MATTER WAS REFERRED TO UPRR SPECIAL AGENT K.C. DECHANT FOR INSPECTION.  DECHANT INSPECTED THE CAR, NOTING LIQUID COMING FROM BENEATH THE VALVE COVER, WHICH WAS UNDER THE PROTECTION OF SEAL "KOCH REFINING 152326".  SEAL WAS REMOVED AND VALVE ASSEMBLY INSPECTED, WITH PRODUCT NOTED TO BE COMING IN THREE SMALL STREAMS FROM THE INTERFACE BETWEEN THE LIQUID VALVE AND THE LIQUID SIPHON PIPE.  MATERIAL APPEARED TO BE ESCAPING UNDER PRESSURE.  THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS THEN OPENED, WITH SUBSTANTIAL VAPOR RELEASE NOTED.  THE VAPOR WAS ALLOWED TO BLEED OFF THROUGH THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE FOR APPROXIMATELY 1-2 MINUTES UNTIL ALL PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED.  AT THAT TIME IT WAS NOTED THAT THE LEAK HAD SUBSIDED AT THE LIQUID VALVE.  INSPECTION OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS DISCLOSED ALL WERE SECURE EXCEPT FOR A BALL VALVE MOUNTED ON THE SIPHON PIPE.  THE AIR INLET VALVE, LOCATED IMMEDIATELY ADJACENT TO THE BALL VALVE/SIPHON PIPE ASSEMBLY, WAS EQUIPPED WITH A RELATIVELY LONG PORT PLUG WHICH, WHEN INSTALLED, WOULD NOT ALLOW COMPLETE TIGHTENING OF LIQUID BALL VALVE, AS THE VALVE STEM ON THE LIQUID VALVE WOULD NOT CLEAR THE AIR INLET PORT PLUG.  DECHANT REMOVED THE LIQUID VALVE AND THE AIR INLET PORT PLUG. ALL THREADS WERE FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION, ALTHOUGH NO THREAD SEALING MATERIAL HAD BEEN IN USE.  THE LIQUID VALVE WAS REINSTALLED WITH TEFLON TAPE ON THE TRHEADS, AFTER WHICH THE AIR INLET PLUG WAS REINSTALLED.  THE PRODUCT LEVEL IN THE CAR WAS CHECKED, AND THERE WAS NO INDICATION THE CAR HAD BEEN OVERLOADED.  MANWAY GASKET SHOWED ONLY SLIGHT DETERIORATION, WAS PLIABLE, AND SUITABLE FOR USE.  SEAL "KOCH REFINING 152325" WAS REMOVED FOR THIS INSPECTION, REPLACED WITH "UPE-277486" WHEN COMPLETED. VALVE COVER WAS RESEALED WITH "UPE-277489" PRIOR TO RELEASING CAR FOR MOVEMENT AT 1450 HRS.

ON JANUARY 21, 1997 SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT E.R. FEDRICK WAS ADVISED BY CTS MANAGER TOM ROBINSON THAT TANKCAR UTLX 910617 IN THE LIVONIA YARD HAD BEEN REPORTED TO HAVE A SLIGHT LEAK NEAR THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  FEDRICK CONTACTED THE MYO IN LIVONIA, WAYNE WOODAL AND REQUESTED THE CAR BE PLACED IN A REMOTE AREA OF THE YARD, PENDING AN INSPECTION.  WOODAL WAS ASKED TO CONTACT THE STATE AND ADVISE THEM OF THE INCIDENT.  UPON ARRIVAL AT LIVONIA, FEDRICK FOUND THAT A CREW FROM THE SHIPPER UNION CARBIDE, HAD RESOLVED THE PROBLEM.  SPECIALISTS JIMMY ELLIS AND MILTON FREY WITH UNION CARBIDE ADVISED FEDRICK THAT THE "A" END VALVE PLUG WAS COMPLETELY OUT OF THE SCREW WELL AND LYING ON THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  AS A RESULT, ICE HAD FORMED IN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  THE MELTING ICE HAD BEEN THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  UNION CARBIDE PERSONNEL REPLACED THE VALVE PLUG AND CHECKED ALL OTHER FITTINGS TO ENSURE THAT THE TANKCAR WAS SECURE.  STATE DEQ AGENT, KAREN J. GEESEY WAS ALSO AT THE SCENE AND APPROVED OF THE HANDLING AND RESOLUTION OF THE INCIDENT.  MYO WOODAL WAS ADVISED THAT THE CAR WAS SECURED AND COULD BE RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, WAS NOTIFIED BY ONE SPOT FOREMEN, THAT A STRONG MTBE ODOR WAS COMING FROM TANKCAR GETX 3108. ALSO, ALL EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED FROM ONE SPOT. CHRISTIE STATED THAT TRAILER BMDZ 635146 HAD ARRIVED AT HIS FACILITY VIA WESTERN PORTS TRANSPORTATION AND HE WAS REFUSING TO ACCEPT THE TRAILER DUE TO A LEAKING TOTE IN THE LEFT DOORWAY OF THE TRAILER. THIS ACTION CAUSED THE TRUCK TO BRAKE ABRUPTLY AND STARTED THE TRAILER IN TO A "JACK-KNIFE".  OUR TRAILER LEFT THE EDGE OF THE ROAD AND OVERTURNED ONTO THE SHOULDER.  WHEN THE CARGO TANK PULL TRAILER ROLLED OVER, IT ROLLED OVER SOME DEBRIS(ROCKS) ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE CARGO TANK WAS LOST THROUGH THE PUNCTURE/CRACK ON THE VESSEL.  AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT THE CONTAMINATED SOIL HAS BEEN EXCAVATED AND TRANSPORTED TO A WASTE/TSD SITE FOR REMEDIATION.  THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST(S) HAVE NOT BEEN FORWARDED TO MY OFFICE AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT. IF YOU SHOULD NEED ADDITIONAL INFORMATION PLEASE CALL ME AT (800)477-1217.

column168: ON JANUARY 22, 1997 A TRACTOR/TRAILER OWNED/OPERATED BY MP ENVIRONMENTAL LEFT PHOENIX BOUND FOR HENDERSON, CO.  AT APPROXIMATELY 15:00 PM THE DRIVER STOPPED NEAR WINSLOW, AZ AT EXIT 253 AT THE PILOT TRUCK STOP.  THE DRIVER RETURNED TO HIS TRUCK AT APPX 15:30 PM AND PERFORMED THE USUAL WALK-AROUND INSPECTION AND TIRE CHECK REQUIRED BY DOT.  DURING THE WALK-AROUND INSPECTION, THE DRIVER NOTICED AN UNUSUAL ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  HE INSPECTED THE TRAILER AND NOTICED SOME SMALL DROPLETS DRIPPING OUT OF THE TRUCK INTO THE ASPHALT.  AT THIS TIME HE CALLED HIS DISPATCHER - STEVE MOONEY AND ADVISED HIM OF THE INCIDENT.  STEVE THEN CALLED ADVANCED ENVIRONMENTAL TECHNICAL SERVICES AND SPOKE TO MATT MORRIS WHO DISPATCHED A CREW TO RESPOND TO STABILIZE THE SCENE AND CLEAN ANY SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE RESPONDING TEAM ARRIVED AT APPX 21:00 PM ON THE 22ND.  IT WAS FOUND THAT APPX 2.5 GALS OF 49% HYDROFLUORIC ACID HAD LEAKED FROM A LAB PACK CONTAINER.  THIS WAS A LABPACK OF A 5 GAL CAPACITY POLY BUNG TOP "CARBOY" BUCKET WHICH HAD BEEN HALF FULL.  THE POLY BUCKET HAD FAILED TO SEAL AROUND THE BUNG AND HAD TIPPED OVER AT ABOUT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE INSIDE THE OUTER CONTAINER (DOT 55 GAL STEEL DRUM).  THE TWO POLY LINERS ALSO FAILED TO CONTAIN THE ACID WITHIN THE STEEL DRUM.  MOST OF THE 2.5 GAL WAS CONTAINED EITHER BY THE ABSORBENT AROUND THE PRIMARY CONTAINER WITHIN THE LABPACK, OR WITHIN THE BED OF THE TRUCK WHICH WAS DESIGNED AS A CONTAINMENT TRAILER.  THE CAPACITY OF THE TRAILER IS IN EXCESS OF 100 GALS BUT APPARENTLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF HYDROFLUORIC ACID FOUND A SEAM TO LEAK THROUGH SLIGHTLY.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE SLIGHT DRIP AS SOON AS IT WAS DISCOVERED.  THE LIQUIDS INSIDE THE TRUCK WERE ABSORBED UP AND THE LEAKY/CONTAMINATED CONTAINER WAS OVERPACKED INTO A DOT POLY 85 GAL DRUM. THE ASPHALT AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED AND THE PH OF THE AREA WAS TAKEN AFTER CLEAN-UP TO VERIFY THAT THE CLEAN-UP HAD BEEN EFFECTIVE.  AETS HAS ALREADY TAKEN STEPS TO ENSURE THAT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN. AETS AS A BEST MANAGEMENT PRACTICE NOW REQUIRES THAT CONCENTRATED ACID LABPACKS NOW BE PACKAGED INTO POLY CONTAINERS AND THAT THE INTEGRITY OF THE INNER CONTAINER BE VERIFIED.  AETS ALSO REQUIRES THAT INNER CONTAINERS BE PACKAGED SO THAT THEY ARE NOT PRONE TO TIPPING OVER.

column168: SIDNEY TAPPER WAS UNLOADING THE SKID OF FREIGHT.  HE WAS TRYING TO MOVE THE SKID WITH A FORKLIFT TO MOVE OVER SO ANOTHER UNLOADER WITH A FORKLIFT AND FREIGHT COULD PASS BY.  HE ACCIDENTALLY PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE SKID, AND THE LIQUID (CORROSIVE 8) STARTED FLOWING OUT ONTO THE EAST SIDE OF THE DOCK AROUND DOOR 36.  SIDNEY TAPPER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED ME (BARRY MCLEMORE) AND STEVE EICHNER (FOS).  I (BARRY) SEALED THE AREA AROUND THE SPILLAGE WITH LOOSE SKIDS.  STEVE AND SIDNEY MOVED THE HAZ MAT MATERIALS OVER TO THE AREA OF SPILLAGE (DOOR 36).  I (BARRY) POURED AROUND 3 - 40 LBS BAGS OF OIL DRY MATERIAL ONTO THE SPILLAGE.  WE ALL STABILIZED THE GROUND WHERE THE SPILLAGE OCCURRED.  WE LEFT THE AREA SEALED AND CLEANED UP THE HAZ MAT SPILL PROPERLY.

column168: ON JANUARY 15, 1997, AT AROUND 05:00, ADM OWNER/OPERATOR, JOHN E. KISSLING, DRIVING TRACTOR-TRAILER 045180-A92017 (HEREIN REFERRED TO AS VEHICLE #1), WAS INVOLVED IN A ROLLOVER ACCIDENT.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON NORTHBOUND I-380, MILEMARKER 66.35, AT EXIT 66, BETWEEN GILBERTVILLE, IOWA AND RAYMOND, IOWA.  MR KISSLING'S CARGO WAS DENATURED (FUEL) ALCOHOL, 3, NA1987, II.  MR. KISSLING HAD PICKED HIS LOAD UP AT ADM, CEDAR RAPIDS, IOWA, AND WAS TO DELIVER SAME TO CSI, KOCH REFINING, ROSEVILLE, MINNESOTA. INTERSTATE-380 IS A FOUR LANE, DIVIDED HIGHWAY, AT THIS LOCATION, WITH TWO LANES NORTHBOUND AND TWO LANES SOUTHBOUND.  THERE WAS HEAVY SNOW AND STRONG WINDS IN THE AREA AND THE ROAD SURFACE WAS SNOW COVERED AND ICY. DRIVER #1 WAS ABLE TO PULL HIMSELF OUT OF THE OVERTURNED TRACTOR AND STAYED BY SAME UNTIL INITIAL ASSISTANCE ARRIVED.  (I.E., TWO TRACTOR-TRAILER DRIVERS STOPPED).  THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE CALLED, VIA A CELLULAR PHONE PROVIDED BY ONE OF DRIVERS WHO STOPPED TO ASSIST (THIS DRIVER, MR. DALE SMITH, 905 19TH AVENUE, CEDAR RAPIDS, IOWA, WITNESSED THE ENTIRE EVENT AND CORROBORATED DRIVER #1'S ACCOUNT OF SAME).  DRIVER #1 ALSO CONTACTED ADM TRUCKING, DISPATCH (AT 05:15) IN DECATUR, ILLINOIS TO REPORT THE ACCIDENT. DRIVER #1 REPORTS HE SUSTAINED A BRUSIED SHOULDER AS A RESULT OF THE ROLLOVER, BUT DID NOT REQUIRE MEDICAL ATTENTION AWAY FROM THE SCENE. ADM WAS IN CONTACT WITH LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICALS OF THE BLACK HAWK COUNTY SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT THROUGHOUT THE ORDEAL.  SHERIFF'S DEPUTIES SUPPLIED EARLY ON-SITE INFORMATION AND WERE KEPT APPRAISED OF CONTAINMENT, RECOVERY AND CLEAN-UP EFFORTS BEING COORDINATED THROUGH ADM, DECATUR.  THE SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT INFORMED ADM THAT THE INTERSTATE (I-380) WOULD REMAIN OPEN UNTIL EFFORTS TO RIGHT THE TRAILER AND PRODUCT TRANSFER OCCURRED. INTERSTATE-380 WAS CLEANED AROUND 9:30.  THE SOUTHBOUND SIDE WAS REOPENED AT 12:29.  THE NORTHBOUND LANES WERE KEPT CLOSED UNTIL THE PRODUCT TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AND THE AREA WAS CLEARED OF WRECKAGE.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MGR, CHEMICAL TRANS SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY DENNY YARD, OPERATIONS MGR, INTERMINAL SERVICES, UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CA, WHO STATED ONE OF HIS CRANE OPERATORS HAD OBSERVED A CONTAINER LEAKING AS IT WAS BEING REMOVED FROM THE RAIL CAR.  AS THE CONTAINER WAS A PLACARDED COMMODITY, IT WAS MOVED TO TRAILER STORAGE LOT #16 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  CONTAINER TRLU 482435, ARRIVED LOS ANGELES ON THE CHLA6X-18, AT 0550 HRS, TUE, 1/21/97.  MGR COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND OBSERVED WHAT APPEARED TO BE A PINK COLORED PAINT MATERIAL LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOORING, NEAR THE FORWARD PORTION OF THE CONTAINER, DIRECTLY BEHIND THE CHASSIS LANDING GEAR.  SEAL XXXX XXXXXXX WAS REMOVED, AND THE REAR DOORS OPENED TO INSPECT THE LADING.  A TOYOTA CAMRY WAS LOCATED IN THE REAR HALF OF THE CONTAINER, WITH THE MIXED FREIGHT AND HAZ MAT LOCATED IN THE FORWARD PORTION OF THE CONTAINER. UPON REACHING THE FORWARD SECTION OF THE CONTAINER, OBSERVED A MAKE SHIFT BRACE MADE OF 2X4'S AND 4X4'S, ALL OF WHICH WAS SUPPORTED BY 2 EACH, 12 FOOT 2X4'S THAT WERE NAILED TO THE BRACE AT THE CENTER, AND RAN THE LENGTH OF THE CONTAINER, DOWN THE SIDE OF THE AUTOMOBILE, WHERE IT WAS NAILED TO THE FLOORING.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PRACTICE FOR SECURING FREIGHT, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD FOR THE BLOCKING AND BRACING OF HAZ MAT, PER BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 6C. ************************  4 EACH, 30 GALLON METAL DRUMS, WERE OBSERVED LOADED ON THE FLOOR DIRECTLY BEHIND THE BRACING.  THEY HAD BEEN PLACED IN A 4X4X4 PATTERN ACROSS THE WIDTH OF THE CONTAINER, WHICH LEFT VERY LARGE VOIDS BETWEEN THE DRUMS AND THE SIDES OF THE CONTAINER.  THE FLOORING WAS COVERED WITH THE PAINT MATERIAL WHERE THE DRUMS WERE SITTING.  PALLETS OF ADDITIONAL PAINT MATERIAL IN 10 GALLON METAL PAILS HAD BEEN PLACED ON TOP OF THE METAL DRUMS WITH NO BI-LEVEL SEPARATION, AND THERE WAS ADDITIONAL FREIGHT MIXED IN WITH THE HAZ MAT. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PRACTICE AND DOES NOT MEET THE REQUIREMENTS FOR COMMODITY SEGREGATION AND BI-LEVEL SEPARATION FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZ MAT PER BOE 6C.  **************** AS THERE WAS NO SECUREMENT OF THE METAL DRUMS, THEY MOVED DURING TRANSIT, WHICH ALLOWED FOR ADDITIONAL VOIDS, RESULTING IN THE UPPER LEVEL PALLETS TOPPLING OFF OF THE DRUMS. ALSO, DUE TO THE WEIGHT OF THE PAINT MATERIAL IN THE PAILS, AND NO BI-LEVEL SEPARATION, 2 OF THE DRUMS WERE CRUSHED AND FAILED AT THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP FROM THE DRUM COLLASPING.  1 PAIL FAILED FROM TOPPLING FROM THE PALLET AND ABRASION FROM ADJACENT FREIGHT.  APPX 1 GALLON OF LIQUID WAS LOST FROM THE PAIL, AND IT WAS ABSORBED INTO THE ADJACENT FREIGHT. BOTH OF THE DRUMS LOST APPX 7-10 GALLONS EACH.  AS THE LADING WAS FOR LOCAL DELIVERY, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE AUTOMOBILE HAULED AWAY, AND THE REMAINING FREIGHT WAS PLACED INTO CONTAINER TPHU 515964, WHICH APL PROVIDED FROM THEIR HARBOR FACILITY.  THE DAMAGED METAL DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACK DRUMS AND SENT ON TO
