column168: ON JANUARY 8, 1997, PASSENGER ALFREDO GONZALEZ, WENT OUT ON FLIGHT 5533 TO SANTO DOMINGO, D.R.., FLIGHT DEPARTED MAYAGUES AT 0845 AND RETURNED TO MAYAGUEZ, FIFTEEN MINUTES LATER, AFTER CAPT. OSWALD PERKINS NOTICED A STRONG SMELL OF FUEL FUMES IN THE CABIN.  AFTER RETURNING TO THE AIRPORT PASSENGER VOLUNTARILY ADVISED THAT THE MATERIAL HAD SPILLED OVER HIS HAND CARRY-ON.  PASSENGER WAS DEPLANED AND QUESTIONED ABOUT THE CONTENTS OF HIS CARRY ON AND HE SAID THAT HE WAS UNAWARE THAT HE HAD THAT CONTAINER IN HIS CARRY-ON, THAT MAYBE HE PACKED TO FAST AND MISTAKENLY PUT IT INSIDE THE BAG.  AS A RESULT OF THIS FAILURE, ALL PERSONNEL WAS BRIEFED AND RE-TRAINED ON AIRPORT SECURITY MEASURES, DANGEROUS GOODS TRANSPORTATION AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS AND REQUIREMENTS. CAPT. TEODORO SANTIESTEBAN, DIRECTOR OF SAFETY, CONDUCTED THIS TRAINING IN MAYAGUES.  WE AT EXECUTIVE AIRLINES INC., ARE COMMITTED TO HIGH STANDARDS OF SAFETY AND SECURITY AND WILL DO ALL POSSIBLE TO AVOID ANY RE-OCCURRENCES.
column172: Plastic container, no capacity or description given

column168: DURING THE SORT, THE DRUM WAS DROPPED.  UPON IMPACT WITH THE CEMENT FLOOR, THE DRUM CRACKED ALONG THE SEAM ALLOWING A SMALL SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL TO ESCAPE.  THE SPILL WAS RECOVERED.  THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND OVERPACKED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE FREIGHT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

ON OPERATIONS DATE, 01/28/97, SORT LEAD, LINDA WILSON CALLED VIA RADIO TO HAZ MAT BASE AND REPORTED THAT SHE HAD A PACKAGE THAT WAS LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR OF ALCOHOL UP IN PRIMARY "8" OF BUILDING "C" AT DIVERTER "8". UPON ARRIVAL, THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION WAS OBSERVED TO BE LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID AND THE ODOR OF ALCOHOL WAS NOTED TO BE PRESENT. SPILL TECHNICIAN, WAYNE HOGSETT DONNED A CARTRIDGE MASK AND OPENED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION. UPON VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, THE FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE FOUND: 3 X 8 OUNCE AEROSOL CANS OF BRUT HAIR CONTROL,  2 X 12 OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES OF JHERI REDDING HAIR SPRAY "UNSCENTED" NOTE: 1 OF THE TWO 12 OUNCES PLASTIC RECEPTACLES LEAKED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS MANUFACTURES WARNING STATED "FLAMMABLE" DUE TO THE ALCOHOL CONTENT NON HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES IN THE PACKAGE ARE AS FOLLOWS: 1 X 16 OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE OF JHERI REDDING "MICA GEL" - 2 X 32 OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES OF MAGICAL MANE CONDITIONER. VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE OUTER PACKAGING IT WAS NOTED THAT THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS INDICATING THAT THE INNER CONTENTS WERE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND TAKEN TO OUR HAZMAT SORT WHERE IT WAS PLACED IN OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE OHIO MOTOR CARRIERS AUTHORITIES.

AT 5:45 MURRAY SUMMONED ME TO THE CLERK AREA FOR A HAZ MAT SPILL. I DONNED PROPER PPE, EVALUATED THE PKG AND FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR A CORROSIVE LIQUID I ABSORBED SPILLAGE WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE TO REDUCE PH LEVEL.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1220 HOURS, ON SATURDAY, JANUARY 25, 1997, BRAD RAMSEY, THE APRIA HEALTHCARE EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT, WAS STANDING BY AN APRIA TRUCK TO WHICH HE HAD BEEN ASSIGNED AS A DRIVER'S HELPER. MR. RAMSEY TRANSFERRED APPROXIMATELY 1.5 LIQUID LITERS OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, FROM A LIQUID OXYGEN HOME UNIT, TO A TWO LITER PLASTIC SODA BOTTLE. HE PLACED THE TOP ON THE BOTTLE AND PLACED THE BOTTLE IN A VACANT LOT AT 2036 NORTH HOWARD STREET, PHILADELPHIA, PA. HE THEN LEFT THE AREA WITH THE DRIVER OF THE APRIA VEHICLE. THE DRIVER WAS NOT AWARE OF MR. RAMSEY'S ACTIONS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1230 HOURS, JANUARY 25, 1997, THE BOTTLE EXPLODED. THE EXPLOSION WAS WITNESSED BY AN OFF DUTY PHILADELPHIA POLICE OFFICER WHO CALLED CHEMTREC. CHEMTREC ADVISED THAT THERE WAS NO CLEAN UP REQUIRED. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE SUSTAINED. LAW ENFORCEMENT DID NOT TAKE A REPORT. APRIA HEALTHCARE WAS CONTACTED BECAUSE THE TRUCK HAD BEEN OBSERVED AT THE SCENE. INVESTIGATION OF THE CIRCUMSTANCES AND MR. RAMSEY'S PARTICIPATION WAS DISCLOSED BY APRIA SUPERVISORS. MR. RAMSEY'S EMPLOYMENT WITH APRIA WAS TERMINATED SHORTLY AFTER THIS INCIDENT. IN ADDITION TO THE FACTS THAT THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO CLEAN UP REQUIRED, PLEASE NOTE THAT THIS INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY ACTIONS TAKEN, AGAINST COMPANY POLICY, BY ONE EMPLOYEE. THE COMPANY THEN PROMPTLY TERMINATED THAT INDIVIDUAL'S EMPLOYMENT. PLEASE BE ADVISED THAT THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE AS IT IS UNCLEAR WHETHER THIS INCIDENT IS COVERED BY THE REPORTING REQUIREMENT OF 49 CFR SECTION 171.16.

column168: MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RICK SLOANE WAS NOTIFIED BY YARD FORCES AT EUGENE, OR. OF TANK CAR GATX 55671 SPLASHING LIQUID FROM TOP WHILE IT WAS BEING MOVED. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED PENDING AN INSPECTION. UPON ARRIVAL, MR. SLOANE DISCOVERED A FAILED RUPTURE DISC IN THE VENT HOUSING. HE REPLACED THIS WITH A NEW DISC (100LB), DECONNED THE TANK CAR, AND RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: MGR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RICK SLOANE WAS NOTIFIED BY HINKLE M.Y.O. D. DODGE OF AN ODOR SURROUNDING TANK CAR BTRX3311 IN RECEIVING TRACK 4 AT HINKLE YARD. THE BILLING INDICATED THE CAR CONTAINED A FLAMMABLE GAS SO MR. SLOANE ADVISED SHUT DOWN OF ALL RECEIVING YARD OPERATIONS UNTIL HIS INVESTIGATION. UPON ARRIVAL MR. SLOANE DISCOVERED THE PACKING GLAND NUT OF THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS LOOSE AND THERE WAS AN AUDIBLE RELEASE OF PROPANE FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. MR. SLOANE TIGHTENED THE PACKING NUT WHICH SECURED THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ON TO DESTINATION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HOURS, 9 JANUARY 1997, ANTHONY ANAYA, THE APRIA HEALTHCARE EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT, WAS DRIVING AN APRIA TRUCK (A 1992 ISUZU) WHEN IT DROVE ONTO THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF NM HIGHWAY 502 W. NEAR MILE MARKER 15. THE VEHICLE STRUCK 77 FEET OF GUARDRAIL.  THE CAB SEPARATED FROM THE VEHICLE AND CAME TO REST ON THE WESTBOUND SHOULDER AGAINST THE GUARDRAIL FACING NORTH WITH THE DRIVER INSIDE.  THE REST OF THE VEHICLE TURNED OVER ONE TIME AND CAME TO REST ABOUT 50 FEET OFF THE ROAD ON ITS LEFT SIDE FACING EAST.  THE VEHICLE CAUGHT FIRE AND BURNED.

column168: ON JANUARY 28, 1997 MR. SCHNEIDER WITH THE FRA WAS ON AN INSPECTION OF DOVE YARD. MR. SCHNEIDER FOUND UTLX 75728 WAS LEAKING ON TOP. CARY AND MYSELF CALLED UNION CAMP AND THEY CAME DOWN AND FIXED THE TOP GASKET. THIS CAR ONLY LEAKED WHEN MOVED. RJ CORMAN INSPECTED ALL CARS THAT CAME FROM UNION CAMP. THESE CARS ARE MOVED LESS THAN 1 MILE & PUT IN YARD. THIS CAR WAS PLACED ON LEASE TRACK ON AUGUST 1996.

THE BOX WAS STRUCK BY OTHER FREIGHT CAUSING IT TO SPILL.  THE BOX AND SPILLED MATERIAL WERE RECOVERED AND ALL OF IT WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE NUMBER ON THE SHIPPING PAPERS WAS CALLED.  WHEN WERE ATTEMPTED TO CALL THAT NUMBER WE GOT AN ANSWERING MACHINE.  I THEN CALLED AND SPOKE WITH THE SHIPPER, COLEMAN HUGHES.  I ASKED MR. HUGHES IF HE HAD EVER BEEN TRAINED AND TESTED AS REQUIRED BY D.O.T. MR. COLEMAN REPLIED HE HAD NOT  ME. COLEMAN THEN CONTINUED TO ASSAIL FEDEX FOR DAMAGING HIS PACKAGE AND NOT TELLING HIM HE NEEDED TO BE TRAINED.  I EXPLAINED THAT ALL OF THE REQUIREMENTS ARE OUTLINED IN OUR SERVICE GUIDE AND THAT PUBLICATIONS IS AVAILABLE FROM ANY MANNED FEDEX LOCATION.  BASED ON MY BELIEF THAT 49 CFR 175.30 HAD BEEN VIOLATED I CALLED THE WESTERN REGION DUTY OFFICER WHO HAD FAA SPECIAL AGENT FRANK WEBB CALL ME BACK.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD AT THE CARSON, CA FEDEX STATION PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.
